[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] If *f* is a Schwartz function, then *τxf* is the convolution with a translated Dirac delta function *τ**x**f* = *f* ∗ *τ**x* *δ*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] So translation invariance of the convolution of Schwartz functions is a consequence of the associativity of convolution.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Furthermore, under certain conditions, convolution is the most general translation invariant operation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Thus some translation invariant operations can be represented as convolution.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Convolutions play an important role in the study of time-invariant systems, and especially LTI system theory.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] The representing function *g**S* is the impulse response of the transformation *S*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] A more precise version of the theorem quoted above requires specifying the class of functions on which the convolution is defined, and also requires assuming in addition that *S* must be a continuous linear operator with respect to the appropriate topology.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] It is known, for instance, that every continuous translation invariant continuous linear operator on *L*1 is the convolution with a finite Borel measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] More generally, every continuous translation invariant continuous linear operator on *L**p* for 1 ≤ *p* < ∞ is the convolution with a tempered distribution whose Fourier transform is bounded.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] To wit, they are all given by bounded Fourier multipliers.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] In typical cases of interest *G* is a locally compact Hausdorff topological group and λ is a (left-) Haar measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] In that case, unless *G* is unimodular, the convolution defined in this way is not the same as ${\textstyle \int f\left(xy^{-1}\right)g(y)\,d\lambda (y)}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Furthermore, the convention is also required for consistency with the definition of the convolution of measures given below.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] However, with a right instead of a left Haar measure, the latter integral is preferred over the former.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] On locally compact abelian groups, a version of the convolution theorem holds: the Fourier transform of a convolution is the pointwise product of the Fourier transforms.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] The circle group **T** with the Lebesgue measure is an immediate example.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] By the commutativity property cited above, *T* is normal: *T** *T* = *TT** .
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Also, *T* commutes with the translation operators.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Consider the family *S* of operators consisting of all such convolutions and the translation operators.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Then *S* is a commuting family of normal operators.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] According to spectral theory, there exists an orthonormal basis {*hk*} that simultaneously diagonalizes *S*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] This characterizes convolutions on the circle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] which are precisely the characters of **T**.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Each convolution is a compact multiplication operator in this basis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] This can be viewed as a version of the convolution theorem discussed above.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] A discrete example is a finite cyclic group of order *n*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Convolution operators are here represented by circulant matrices, and can be diagonalized by the discrete Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Let *G* be a (multiplicatively written) topological group.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] In fact, if *either* measure is absolutely continuous with respect to the Haar measure, then so is their convolution.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] If μ and ν are probability measures on the topological group (**R**,+), then the convolution *μ*∗*ν* is the probability distribution of the sum *X* + *Y* of two independent random variables *X* and *Y* whose respective distributions are μ and ν.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Let (*X*, Δ, ∇, *ε*, *η*) be a bialgebra with comultiplication Δ, multiplication ∇, unit η, and counit *ε*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] The convolution is a product defined on the endomorphism algebra End(*X*) as follows.
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] The convolution appears notably in the definition of Hopf algebras (Kassel 1995, §III.3).
[src:harmonic-analysis/convolution] Convolution and related operations are found in many applications in science, engineering and mathematics.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] A **Fourier series** (/ˈfʊrieɪ, -iər/) is a series expansion of a periodic function into a sum of trigonometric functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series is an example of a trigonometric series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] By expressing a function as a sum of sines and cosines, many problems involving the function become easier to analyze because trigonometric functions are well understood.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] For example, Fourier series were first used by Joseph Fourier to find solutions to the heat equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This application is possible because the derivatives of trigonometric functions fall into simple patterns.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Fourier series cannot be used to approximate arbitrary functions, because most functions have infinitely many terms in their Fourier series, and the series do not always converge.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Well-behaved functions, for example smooth functions, have Fourier series that converge to the original function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The coefficients of the Fourier series are determined by integrals of the function multiplied by trigonometric functions, described in Fourier series § Definition.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The study of the convergence of Fourier series focus on the behaviors of the *partial sums*, which means studying the behavior of the sum as more and more terms from the series are summed.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The figures below illustrate some partial Fourier series results for the components of a square wave.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Fourier series are closely related to the Fourier transform, a more general tool that can even find the frequency information for functions that are *not* periodic.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Periodic functions can be identified with functions on a circle; for this reason Fourier series are the subject of Fourier analysis on the circle group, denoted by $\mathbb {T}$ or $S_{1}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier transform is also part of Fourier analysis, but is defined for functions on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Since Fourier's time, many different approaches to defining and understanding the concept of Fourier series have been discovered, all of which are consistent with one another, but each of which emphasizes different aspects of the topic.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Some of the more powerful and elegant approaches are based on mathematical ideas and tools that were not available in Fourier's time.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Fourier originally defined the Fourier series for real-valued functions of real arguments, and used the sine and cosine functions in the series expansion.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Many other Fourier-related transforms have since been defined, extending his initial idea to many applications and birthing an area of mathematics called Fourier analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series is named in honor of Jean-Baptiste Joseph Fourier (1768–1830), who made important contributions to the study of trigonometric series, after preliminary investigations by Leonhard Euler, Jean le Rond d'Alembert, and Daniel Bernoulli.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The *Mémoire* introduced Fourier analysis, specifically Fourier series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Through Fourier's research the fact was established that an arbitrary (at first, continuous and later generalized to any piecewise-smooth) function can be represented by a trigonometric series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The first announcement of this great discovery was made by Fourier in 1807, before the French Academy.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Early ideas of decomposing a periodic function into the sum of simple oscillating functions date back to the 3rd century BC, when ancient astronomers proposed an empiric model of planetary motions, based on deferents and epicycles.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Independently of Fourier, astronomer Friedrich Wilhelm Bessel introduced Fourier series to solve Kepler's equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] His work was published in 1819, unaware of Fourier's work which remained unpublished until 1822.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The heat equation is a partial differential equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Prior to Fourier's work, no solution to the heat equation was known in the general case, although particular solutions were known if the heat source behaved in a simple way, in particular, if the heat source was a sine or cosine wave.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] These simple solutions are now sometimes called eigensolutions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Fourier's idea was to model a complicated heat source as a superposition (or linear combination) of simple sine and cosine waves, and to write the solution as a superposition of the corresponding eigensolutions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This superposition or linear combination is called the Fourier series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] From a modern point of view, Fourier's results are somewhat informal, due to the lack of a precise notion of function and integral in the early nineteenth century.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Later, Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet and Bernhard Riemann expressed Fourier's results with greater precision and formality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series has many such applications in electrical engineering, vibration analysis, acoustics, optics, signal processing, image processing, quantum mechanics, econometrics, shell theory, etc.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] — Joseph Fourier, Mémoire sur la propagation de la chaleur dans les corps solides (1807).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This immediately gives any coefficient *ak* of the trigonometric series for φ(*y*) for any function which has such an expansion.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] In these few lines, which are close to the modern formalism used in Fourier series, Fourier revolutionized both mathematics and physics.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Although similar trigonometric series were previously used by Euler, d'Alembert, Daniel Bernoulli and Gauss, Fourier believed that such trigonometric series could represent any arbitrary function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] In what sense that is actually true is a somewhat subtle issue and the attempts over many years to clarify this idea have led to important discoveries in the theories of convergence, function spaces, and harmonic analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series expansion of the sawtooth function (below) looks more complicated than the simple formula $s(x)={\tfrac {x}{\pi }}$ , so it is not immediately apparent why one would need the Fourier series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] While there are many applications, Fourier's motivation was in solving the heat equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] For example, consider a metal plate in the shape of a square whose sides measure $\pi$ meters, with coordinates $(x,y)\in [0,\pi ]\times [0,\pi ]$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Here, $\sinh$ is the hyperbolic sine function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This solution of the heat equation is obtained by multiplying each term of the equation from Analysis § Example by $\sinh(ny)/\sinh(n\pi )$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] While our example function $s(x)$ seems to have a needlessly complicated Fourier series, the heat distribution $T(x,y)$ is nontrivial.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The function T cannot be written as a closed-form expression.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This method of solving the heat problem was made possible by Fourier's work.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Another application is to solve the Basel problem by using Parseval's theorem.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The example generalizes and one may compute ζ(2*n*), for any positive integer *n*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] However, these are not necessary conditions and there are many theorems about different types of convergence of Fourier series (e.g. uniform convergence or mean convergence).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The definition naturally extends to the Fourier series of a (periodic) distribution s (also called *Fourier-Schwartz series*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Then the Fourier series converges to $s(x)$ in the distribution sense.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The process of determining the Fourier coefficients of a given function or signal is called ***analysis***, while forming the associated trigonometric series (or its various approximations) is called ***synthesis***.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The harmonics are indexed by an integer, $n,$ which is also the number of cycles the corresponding sinusoids make in interval P .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] These series can represent functions that are just a sum of one or more frequencies in the harmonic spectrum.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] In the limit $N\to \infty$ , a trigonometric series can also represent the intermediate frequencies or non-sinusoidal functions because of the infinite number of terms.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The coefficients can be given/assumed, such as a music synthesizer or time samples of a waveform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] In the latter case, the exponential form of Fourier series synthesizes a discrete-time Fourier transform where variable x represents frequency instead of time.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] In general, the coefficients are determined by *analysis* of a given function $s(x)$ whose domain of definition is an interval of length P .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The ${\tfrac {2}{P}}$ scale factor follows from substituting **Eq.1** into **Eq.3** and utilizing the orthogonality of the trigonometric system.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] with $c_{0}$ being the mean value of s on the interval P .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This is a particular instance of the Dirichlet theorem for Fourier series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This example leads to a solution of the Basel problem.
