[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This table shows some mathematical operations in the time domain and the corresponding effect in the Fourier series coefficients.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] If s is a P -periodic function on $\mathbb {R}$ which is k times differentiable, and its $k^{\text{th}}$ derivative is continuous, then s belongs to the function space $C^{k}(\mathbb {R} )$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] One of the interesting properties of the Fourier transform which we have mentioned, is that it carries convolutions to pointwise products.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] If that is the property which we seek to preserve, one can produce Fourier series on any compact group.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Typical examples include those classical groups that are compact.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This generalizes the Fourier transform to all spaces of the form *L*2(*G*), where *G* is a compact group, in such a way that the Fourier transform carries convolutions to pointwise products.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series exists and converges in similar ways to the [−*π*,*π*] case.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] An alternative extension to compact groups is the Peter–Weyl theorem, which proves results about representations of compact groups analogous to those about finite groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] If the domain is not a group, then there is no intrinsically defined convolution.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] However, if X is a compact Riemannian manifold, it has a Laplace–Beltrami operator.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The Laplace–Beltrami operator is the differential operator that corresponds to Laplace operator for the Riemannian manifold X .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Then, by analogy, one can consider heat equations on X .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Since Fourier arrived at his basis by attempting to solve the heat equation, the natural generalization is to use the eigensolutions of the Laplace–Beltrami operator as a basis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This generalizes Fourier series to spaces of the type $L^{2}(X)$ , where X is a Riemannian manifold.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series converges in ways similar to the $[-\pi ,\pi ]$ case.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] A typical example is to take X to be the sphere with the usual metric, in which case the Fourier basis consists of spherical harmonics.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The generalization to compact groups discussed above does not generalize to noncompact, nonabelian groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] However, there is a straightforward generalization to Locally Compact Abelian (LCA) groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This generalizes the Fourier transform to $L^{1}(G)$ or $L^{2}(G)$ , where G is an LCA group.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] If G is compact, one also obtains a Fourier series, which converges similarly to the $[-\pi ,\pi ]$ case, but if G is noncompact, one obtains instead a Fourier integral.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This generalization yields the usual Fourier transform when the underlying locally compact Abelian group is $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] As such, when $\mu \in M$ , the function ${\hat {\mu }}(n)$ is also referred to as a Fourier-Stieltjes transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This follows from an earlier and more concrete representation of a Radon measure (i.e. a locally finite Borel measure) on $\mathbb {R}$ , given by F.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] As the distributional derivative of F is a Radon measure, it is subject to the Lebesgue decomposition and can be expressed as $dF=F'dx+dF_{s}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] If $dF_{s}=0$ the expression reduces to the original definition of the Fourier coefficients, hence a Fourier series is a Fourier-Stieltjes series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The question whether or not $\mu$ exists for a given sequence of $c_{n}$ forms the basis of the trigonometric moment problem.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The Fourier series can be generalized still further from measures to distributions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] If the Fourier coefficients are determined by a distribution $F\in {\mathcal {D}}'$ then the series is sometimes described as a *Fourier-Schwartz series*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] While it is often extremely difficult to decide whether a given series is a Fourier or a Fourier-Stieltjes series, deciding whether or not it is a Fourier-Schwartz series is relatively trivial.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Aside from being useful for solving partial differential equations such as the heat equation, one notable application of Fourier series on the square is in image compression.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] In particular, the JPEG image compression standard uses the two-dimensional discrete cosine transform, a discrete form of the Fourier cosine transform, which uses only cosine as the basis function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] For two-dimensional arrays with a staggered appearance, half of the Fourier series coefficients disappear, due to additional symmetry.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] A three-dimensional Bravais lattice is defined as the set of vectors of the form $\mathbf {R} =n_{1}\mathbf {a} _{1}+n_{2}\mathbf {a} _{2}+n_{3}\mathbf {a} _{3}$ where $n_{i}$ are integers and $\mathbf {a} _{i}$ are three linearly independent but not necessarily orthogonal vectors.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Let us consider some function $f(\mathbf {r} )$ with the same periodicity as the Bravais lattice, *i.e.* $f(\mathbf {r} )=f(\mathbf {R} +\mathbf {r} )$ for any lattice vector $\mathbf {R}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This situation frequently occurs in solid-state physics where $f(\mathbf {r} )$ might, for example, represent the effective potential that an electron "feels" inside a periodic crystal.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] In presence of such a periodic potential, the quantum-mechanical description of the electron results in a periodically modulated plane-wave commonly known as Bloch state.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] As the trigonometric series is a special class of orthogonal system, Fourier series can naturally be defined in the context of Hilbert spaces.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] For example, the space of square-integrable functions on $[-\pi ,\pi ]$ forms the Hilbert space $L^{2}([-\pi ,\pi ])$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Its inner product, defined for any two elements f and g , is given by: $\langle f,g\rangle ={\frac {1}{2\pi }}\int _{-\pi }^{\pi }f(x){\overline {g(x)}}\,dx.$ This space is equipped with the orthonormal basis $\left\{e_{n}=e^{inx}:n\in \mathbb {Z} \right\}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The sine-cosine form follows in a similar fashion.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The density of their span is a consequence of the Stone–Weierstrass theorem, but follows also from the properties of classical kernels like the Fejér kernel.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] In engineering, the Fourier series is generally assumed to converge except at jump discontinuities since the functions encountered in engineering are usually better-behaved than those in other disciplines.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] In particular, if s is continuous and the derivative of $s(x)$ (which may not exist everywhere) is square integrable, then the Fourier series of s converges absolutely and uniformly to $s(x)$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] If a function is square-integrable on the interval $[x_{0},x_{0}+P]$ , then the Fourier series converges to the function almost everywhere.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] It is possible to define Fourier coefficients for more general functions or distributions, in which case pointwise convergence often fails, and convergence in norm or weak convergence is usually studied.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Because of the least squares property, and because of the completeness of the Fourier basis, we obtain an elementary convergence result.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] If s is continuously differentiable, then $(in)S[n]$ is the n th Fourier coefficient of the first derivative $s'$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Since $s'$ is continuous, and therefore bounded, it is square-integrable and its Fourier coefficients are square-summable.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This means that s is absolutely summable.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] This result can be proven easily if s is further assumed to be $\textstyle C^{2}$ , since in that case $\textstyle n^{2}S[n]$ tends to zero as $n\rightarrow \infty$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] More generally, the Fourier series is absolutely summable, thus converges uniformly to s , provided that s satisfies a Hölder condition of order $\alpha >{\tfrac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Since Fourier series have such good convergence properties, many are often surprised by some of the negative results.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] For example, the Fourier series of a continuous *T*-periodic function need not converge pointwise.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] The uniform boundedness principle yields a simple non-constructive proof of this fact.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] In 1922, Andrey Kolmogorov published an article titled *Une série de Fourier-Lebesgue divergente presque partout* in which he gave an example of a Lebesgue-integrable function whose Fourier series diverges almost everywhere.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] He later constructed an example of an integrable function whose Fourier series diverges everywhere.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] As m increases, the coefficients will be positive and increasing until they reach a value of about $C_{m}\approx 2/(n^{2}\pi )$ at $m=2^{n^{3}}/2$ for some n and then become negative (starting with a value around $-2/(n^{2}\pi )$ ) and getting smaller, before starting a new such wave.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] in the nth wave before returning to around zero, showing that the series does not converge at zero but reaches higher and higher peaks.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-series] Note that though the function is continuous, it is not differentiable.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In mathematics, the **Fourier transform** (**FT**) is an integral transform that takes a function as input and outputs another function that describes the extent to which various frequencies are present in the original function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The output of the transform is a complex valued function of frequency.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The term *Fourier transform* refers to both the mathematical operation and to this complex-valued function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When a distinction needs to be made, the output of the operation is sometimes called the frequency domain representation of the original function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform is analogous to decomposing the sound of a musical chord into the intensities of its constituent pitches.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Functions that are localized in the time domain have Fourier transforms that are spread out across the frequency domain and vice versa, a phenomenon known as the uncertainty principle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The critical case for this principle is the Gaussian function, of substantial importance in probability theory and statistics as well as in the study of physical phenomena exhibiting normal distribution (e.g., diffusion).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform of a Gaussian function is another Gaussian function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Joseph Fourier introduced sine and cosine transforms (which correspond to the imaginary and real components of the modern Fourier transform) in his study of heat transfer, where Gaussian functions appear as solutions of the heat equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform can be formally defined as an improper Riemann integral, making it an integral transform, although this definition is not suitable for many applications requiring a more sophisticated integration theory.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] For example, many relatively simple applications use the Dirac delta function, which can be treated formally as if it were a function, but the justification requires a mathematically more sophisticated viewpoint.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform can also be generalized to functions of several variables on Euclidean space, sending a function of 3-dimensional "position space" to a function of 3-dimensional momentum (or a function of space and time to a function of 4-momentum).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This idea makes the spatial Fourier transform very natural in the study of waves, as well as in quantum mechanics, where it is important to be able to represent wave solutions as functions of either position or momentum and sometimes both.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In general, functions to which Fourier methods are applicable are complex-valued, and possibly vector-valued.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The latter is routinely employed to handle periodic functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The fast Fourier transform (FFT) is an algorithm for computing the DFT.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When $f(x)$ is (Lebesgue) integrable over the whole real line, the above integral converges for all $\xi \in \mathbb {R}$ , and ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )$ is a uniformly continuous function of $\xi$ which decays to zero as ⁠ $\xi \to \infty$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, the Fourier transform can also be defined for (generalized) functions for which the Lebesgue integral **Eq.1** does not make sense.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Interpreting the integral suitably (e.g. as an improper integral for locally integrable functions) extends the Fourier transform to functions that are not necessarily integrable over the whole real line.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] More generally, the Fourier transform also applies to generalized functions like the Dirac delta (and all other tempered distributions), in which case it is defined by duality rather than an integral.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The functions f and ${\widehat {f}}$ are referred to as a **Fourier transform pair**.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When the independent variable (⁠ x ⁠) represents *time* (often denoted by ⁠ t ⁠), the transform variable (⁠ $\xi$ ⁠) represents frequency (often denoted by ⁠ f ⁠).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] For example, if time has the unit second, then frequency has the unit hertz.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The transform variable can also be written in terms of angular frequency, ⁠ $\omega =2\pi \xi$ ⁠, with the unit radian per second.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Furthermore, ${\widehat {f}}\in L^{\infty }\cap C_{0}(\mathbb {R} )$ is bounded, uniformly continuous and (by the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma) vanishing at infinity.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Here $C_{0}(\mathbb {R} )$ denotes the space of continuous functions on $\mathbb {R}$ that approach 0 as x approaches positive or negative infinity.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The space $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ is the space of measurable functions for which the norm $\|f\|_{1}$ is finite, modulo the equivalence relation of equality almost everywhere.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform on $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ is one-to-one.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, there is no easy characterization of the image, and thus no easy characterization of the inverse transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In particular, **Eq.2** is no longer valid, as it was stated only under the hypothesis that $f(x)$ was "sufficiently nice" (e.g., $f(x)$ decays with all derivatives).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] While **Eq.1** defines the Fourier transform for (complex-valued) functions in ⁠ $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠, it is not well-defined for other integrability classes, most importantly the space of square-integrable functions ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, the Fourier transform on the dense subspace $L^{1}\cap L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )\subset L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ admits a unique continuous extension to a unitary operator on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This extension is important in part because, unlike the case of ⁠ $L^{1}$ ⁠, the Fourier transform is an automorphism of the space ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In such cases, the Fourier transform can be obtained explicitly by regularizing the integral, and then passing to a limit.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In practice, the integral is often regarded as an improper integral instead of a proper Lebesgue integral, but sometimes for convergence one needs to use weak limit or principal value instead of the (pointwise) limits implicit in an improper integral.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Titchmarsh (1986) and Dym & McKean (1985) each gives three rigorous ways of extending the Fourier transform to square integrable functions using this procedure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] A general principle in working with the $L^{2}$ Fourier transform is that finite linear combinations of Gaussians are dense in ⁠ $L^{1}\cap L^{2}$ ⁠, and the various features of the Fourier transform, such as its unitarity, are easily inferred for Gaussians.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] A feature of the $L^{1}$ Fourier transform is that it is a homomorphism of Banach algebras from $L^{1}$ equipped with the convolution operation to the Banach algebra of continuous functions under the $L^{\infty }$ (supremum) norm.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The conventions chosen in this article are those of harmonic analysis, such that the Fourier transform is both unitary on ⁠ $L^{2}$ ⁠ and an algebra homomorphism from ⁠ ${1}$ ⁠ to ⁠ $L^{\infty }$ ⁠, without renormalizing the Lebesgue measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In 1822, Fourier claimed (see *Joseph Fourier § The Analytic Theory of Heat*) that any function, whether continuous or discontinuous, can be expanded into a series of sines.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] That important work was corrected and expanded upon by others to provide the foundation for the various forms of the Fourier transform used since.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Likewise, the intuitive interpretation of **Eq.1** is that multiplying $f(x)$ by $e^{-i2\pi \xi x}$ has the effect of subtracting $\xi$ from every frequency component of function ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Only the component that was at frequency $\xi$ can produce a non-zero value of the infinite integral, because (at least formally) all the other shifted components are oscillatory and integrate to zero (see *§ Example*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] It is noteworthy how easily the product was simplified using the polar form, and how easily the rectangular form was deduced by an application of Euler's formula.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Euler's formula introduces the possibility of negative ⁠ $\xi$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Only certain complex-valued $f(x)$ have transforms ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}=0,\ \forall \ \xi <0$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] (See *Analytic signal*; a simple example is ⁠ $e^{i2\pi \xi _{0}x}\ (\xi _{0}>0)$ ⁠.) But negative frequency is necessary to characterize all other complex-valued ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠, found in signal processing, partial differential equations, radar, nonlinear optics, quantum mechanics, and others.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] But it cannot determine the actual sign of ⁠ $\xi _{0}$ ⁠, because $\cos(2\pi \xi _{0}x)$ and $\cos(2\pi (-\xi _{0})x)$ are indistinguishable on just the real numbers line.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform of a periodic function cannot be defined using the integral formula directly.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In order for integral in **Eq.1** to be defined the function must be absolutely integrable.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Instead it is common to use Fourier series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] It is possible to extend the definition to include periodic functions by viewing them as tempered distributions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This makes it possible to see a connection between the Fourier series and the Fourier transform for periodic functions that have a convergent Fourier series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In other words, the Fourier transform is a Dirac comb function whose *teeth* are multiplied by the Fourier series coefficients.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform of an integrable function f can be sampled at regular intervals of arbitrary length ⁠ $1/P$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The integrability of f ensures the periodic summation converges.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When $f(x)$ has compact support, $f_{P}(x)$ has a finite number of terms within the interval of integration.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When $f(x)$ does not have compact support, numerical evaluation of $f_{P}(x)$ requires an approximation, such as tapering $f(x)$ or truncating the number of terms.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The frequency variable must have inverse units to the units of the original function's domain (typically named t or ⁠ x ⁠).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] For example, if t is measured in seconds, $\xi$ should be in cycles per second or hertz.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] If the scale of time is in units of $2\pi$ seconds, then another Greek letter $\omega$ is typically used instead to represent angular frequency (where ⁠ $\omega =2\pi \xi$ ⁠) in units of radians per second.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] If using x for units of length, then $\xi$ must be in inverse length, e.g., wavenumbers.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] That is to say, there are two versions of the real line: one that is the range of t and measured in units of ⁠ t ⁠, and the other that is the range of $\xi$ and measured in inverse units to the units of ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] These two distinct versions of the real line cannot be equated with each other.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Therefore, the Fourier transform goes from one space of functions to a different space of functions: functions that have a different domain of definition.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In general, $\xi$ must always be taken to be a linear form on the space of its domain, which is to say that the second real line is the dual space of the first real line.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] (See the article *Linear algebra* for a more formal explanation and for more details.) This point of view becomes essential in generalizations of the Fourier transform to general symmetry groups, including the case of Fourier series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The various definitions resulting from different choices of units differ by various constants.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In other conventions, the Fourier transform has i in the exponent instead of −*i*, and vice versa for the inversion formula.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This convention is common in modern physics and is the default for Wolfram Alpha, and does not mean that the frequency has become negative, since there is no canonical definition of positivity for frequency of a complex wave.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Many of the identities involving the Fourier transform remain valid in those conventions, provided all terms that explicitly involve *i* have it replaced by −*i*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In electrical engineering the letter *j* is typically used for the imaginary unit instead of *i* because *i* is used for current.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When using dimensionless units, the constant factors might not be written in the transform definition.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In probability theory and mathematical statistics, the use of the Fourier—Stieltjes transform is preferred, because many random variables are not of continuous type, and do not possess a density function, and one must treat not functions but distributions, i.e., measures that possess "atoms".
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] From the higher point of view of group characters, which is much more abstract, all these arbitrary choices disappear, as will be explained in the later section of this article, which treats the notion of the Fourier transform of a function on a locally compact abelian group.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Let $f(x)$ and $h(x)$ represent *integrable functions* Lebesgue-measurable on the real line satisfying: $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }|f(x)|\,dx<\infty .$ We denote the Fourier transforms of these functions as ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )$ and ${\widehat {h}}(\xi )$ respectively.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] When the real and imaginary parts of a complex function are decomposed into their even and odd parts, there are four components, denoted below by the subscripts RE, RO, IE, and IO.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In particular, if f is *real*, then ${\widehat {f}}$ is conjugate symmetric (a.k.a.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The integral of f over its domain is the total mass or DC bias of the function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform may be defined in some cases for non-integrable functions, but the Fourier transforms of integrable functions have several strong properties.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, ${\widehat {f}}$ need not be integrable.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] For example, the Fourier transform of the rectangular function, which is integrable, is the sinc function, which is not Lebesgue integrable, because its improper integrals behave analogously to the alternating harmonic series, in converging to a sum without being absolutely convergent.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] It is not generally possible to write the *inverse transform* as a Lebesgue integral.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, when both f and ${\widehat {f}}$ are integrable, the inverse equality $f(x)=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }{\widehat {f}}(\xi )e^{i2\pi x\xi }\,d\xi$ holds for almost every x.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] As a result, the Fourier transform is injective on *L*1(**R**).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Let ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ and ⁠ $g(x)$ ⁠ be integrable, and let ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\widehat {g}}$ ⁠ be their Fourier transforms.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Plancherel's theorem makes it possible to extend the Fourier transform, by a continuity argument, to a unitary operator on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Plancherel's theorem has the interpretation in the sciences that the Fourier transform preserves the energy of the original quantity.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The terminology of these formulas is not quite standardised.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Parseval's theorem was proved only for Fourier series, and was first proved by Lyapunov.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] But Parseval's formula makes sense for the Fourier transform as well, and so even though in the context of the Fourier transform it was proved by Plancherel, it is still often referred to as Parseval's formula, or Parseval's relation, or even Parseval's theorem.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] See *Pontryagin duality* for a general formulation of this concept in the context of locally compact abelian groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform translates between convolution and multiplication of functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In linear time invariant (LTI) system theory, it is common to interpret ⁠ $g(x)$ ⁠ as the impulse response of an LTI system with input ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ and output ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠, since substituting the unit impulse for ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ yields ⁠ $h(x)=g(x)$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In this case, ⁠ ${\widehat {g}}(\xi )$ ⁠ represents the frequency response of the system.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Conversely, if ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ can be decomposed as the product of two square integrable functions ⁠ $p(x)$ ⁠ and ⁠ $q(x)$ ⁠, then the Fourier transform of ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ is given by the convolution of the respective Fourier transforms ⁠ ${\widehat {p}}(\xi )$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\widehat {q}}(\xi )$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Suppose *f*(*x*) is differentiable almost everywhere, and both ⁠ f ⁠ and its derivative ⁠ $f'$ ⁠ are integrable (in ⁠ $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] By applying the Fourier transform and using these formulas, some ordinary differential equations can be transformed into algebraic equations, which are much easier to solve.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] These formulas also give rise to the rule of thumb "⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠ is smooth if and only if ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )$ ⁠ quickly falls to ⁠ 0 ⁠ for ⁠ $\vert \xi \vert \to \infty$ ⁠".
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Fourier transform is a linear transform that has eigenfunctions obeying ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}[\psi ]=\lambda \psi$ ⁠, with ⁠ $\lambda \in \mathbb {C}$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In other words, every solution $\psi (x)$ and its Fourier transform ${\widehat {\psi }}(\xi )$ obey the same equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Assuming uniqueness of the solutions, every solution $\psi (x)$ must therefore be an eigenfunction of the Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The simplest allowable $U(x)=x$ leads to the standard normal distribution.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The simplest example is provided by ⁠ $W(x)=x^{2}$ ⁠, which is equivalent to considering the Schrödinger equation for the quantum harmonic oscillator.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The corresponding solutions provide an important choice of an orthonormal basis for *L*2(**R**) and are given by the "physicist's" Hermite functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In other words, the Hermite functions form a complete orthonormal system of eigenfunctions for the Fourier transform on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] However, this choice of eigenfunctions is not unique.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Because of ${\mathcal {F}}^{4}=\mathrm {id}$ there are only four different eigenvalues of the Fourier transform (the fourth roots of unity ⁠ $\pm 1$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\pm i$ ⁠) and any linear combination of eigenfunctions with the same eigenvalue gives another eigenfunction.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] As a consequence of this, it is possible to decompose *L*2(**R**) as a direct sum of four spaces *H*0, *H*1, *H*2, and *H*3 where the Fourier transform acts on H*k* simply by multiplication by *i**k*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This approach to define the Fourier transform was first proposed by Norbert Wiener.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Among other properties, Hermite functions decrease exponentially fast in both frequency and time domains, and they are thus used to define a generalization of the Fourier transform, namely the fractional Fourier transform used in time–frequency analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In physics, this transform was introduced by Edward Condon.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This change of basis becomes possible because the Fourier transform is a unitary transform when using the right conventions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] It can be interpreted as the generator of fractional Fourier transforms for arbitrary values of t, and of the conventional continuous Fourier transform ${\mathcal {F}}$ for the particular value ⁠ $t=\pi /2$ ⁠, with the Mehler kernel implementing the corresponding active transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The eigenfunctions of N are the Hermite functions ⁠ $\psi _{n}(x)$ ⁠, which are therefore also eigenfunctions of ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Upon extending the Fourier transform to distributions the Dirac comb is also an eigenfunction of the Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Under suitable conditions on the function ⁠ f ⁠, it can be recovered from its Fourier transform ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] In particular the Fourier transform is invertible (under suitable conditions).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] These are not true for all functions, but are true under various conditions, which are the content of the various forms of the Fourier inversion theorem.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This fourfold periodicity of the Fourier transform is similar to a rotation of the plane by 90°, particularly as the two-fold iteration yields a reversal, and in fact this analogy can be made precise.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This can be further generalized to linear canonical transformations, which can be visualized as the action of the special linear group SL2(**R**) on the time–frequency plane, with the preserved symplectic form corresponding to the uncertainty principle, below.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] This approach is particularly studied in signal processing, under time–frequency analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The Heisenberg group is a certain group of unitary operators on the Hilbert space *L*2(**R**) of square integrable complex valued functions f on the real line, generated by the translations (*Ty f*)(*x*) = *f* (*x* + *y*) and multiplication by *e**i*2π*ξx*, (*Mξ f*)(*x*) = *e**i*2π*ξx* *f* (*x*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] These operators do not commute, as their (group) commutator is $\left(M_{\xi }^{-1}T_{y}^{-1}M_{\xi }T_{y}f\right)(x)=e^{i2\pi \xi y}f(x),$ which is multiplication by the constant (independent of x) *e**i*2π*ξy* ∈ *U*(1) (the circle group of unit modulus complex numbers).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] The above procedure describes not only the group structure, but also a standard unitary representation of *H*1 on a Hilbert space, which we denote by *ρ* : *H*1 → *B*(*L*2(**R**)).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Define the linear automorphism of **R**2 by $J{\begin{pmatrix}x\\\xi \end{pmatrix}}={\begin{pmatrix}-\xi \\x\end{pmatrix}}$ so that *J*2 = −*I*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] According to the Stone–von Neumann theorem, the unitary representations ρ and *ρ* ∘ *j* are unitarily equivalent, so there is a unique intertwiner *W* ∈ *U*(*L*2(**R**)) such that $\rho \circ j=W\rho W^{*}.$ This operator W is the Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] Many of the standard properties of the Fourier transform are immediate consequences of this more general framework.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p01] For example, the square of the Fourier transform, *W*2, is an intertwiner associated with *J*2 = −*I*, and so we have (*W*2*f*)(*x*) = *f* (−*x*) is the reflection of the original function f.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The integral for the Fourier transform ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }e^{-2i\pi t\xi }f(t)\,dt$ can be studied for complex values of its argument ξ.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Depending on the properties of f, this might not converge off the real axis at all, or it might converge to a complex analytic function for all values of *ξ* = *σ* + *iτ*, or something in between.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] (In this case, f is supported on [−*a*, *a*].) This can be expressed by saying that *f̂* is an entire function that is rapidly decreasing in σ (for fixed τ) and of exponential growth in τ (uniformly in σ).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] (If f is not smooth, but only *L*2, a corresponding version holds with the rapid-decrease condition replaced by the appropriate *L*2 condition.) The space of such functions of a complex variable is called the Paley–Wiener space.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This theorem has been generalised to semisimple Lie groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] If f is supported on the half-line *t* ≥ 0, then f is said to be "causal" because the impulse response function of a physically realisable filter must have this property, as no effect can precede its cause.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Paley and Wiener showed that then, under suitable integrability hypotheses, *f̂* extends to a holomorphic function on the complex lower half-plane *τ* < 0 that tends to zero as τ goes to −∞.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] A simple converse in this form is false; precise converses require additional growth or Hardy-space hypotheses.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform *f̂*(*ξ*) is related to the Laplace transform *F*(*s*), which is also used for the solution of differential equations and the analysis of filters.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] It may happen that a function f for which the Fourier integral does not converge on the real axis at all nevertheless has a complex Fourier transform defined in some region of the complex plane.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] If f is causal and the integrals converge, then ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}(i\tau )=F(-2\pi \tau )$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Thus, extending the Fourier transform to the complex domain means it includes the Laplace transform as a special case in the case of causal functions—but with the change of variable *s* = *i*2π*ξ*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] From another, perhaps more classical viewpoint, the Laplace transform by its form involves an additional exponential regulating term that lets it converge outside of the imaginary line where the Fourier transform is defined.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] As such it can converge for functions and integrals with at most exponential growth in the regulated direction, whereas the original Fourier decomposition cannot, enabling analysis of systems with divergent or critical elements.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Two particular examples from linear signal processing are the construction of allpass filter networks from critical comb and mitigating filters via exact pole-zero cancellation on the unit circle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Such designs are common in audio processing, where highly nonlinear phase response is sought for, as in reverb.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Furthermore, when extended pulselike impulse responses are sought for signal processing work, the easiest way to produce them is to have one circuit that produces a divergent time response, and then to cancel its divergence through a delayed opposite and compensatory response.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] There, only the delay circuit in-between admits a classical Fourier description, which is critical.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Both the circuits to the side are unstable, and do not admit a convergent Fourier decomposition.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] However, they do admit a Laplace domain description, with compatible half-planes of convergence in the complex plane (or in the discrete case, the Z-plane), wherein their effects cancel.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In modern mathematics the Laplace transform is conventionally subsumed under the aegis of Fourier methods.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Both of them are subsumed by the far more general, and more abstract, idea of harmonic analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Therefore, the Fourier inversion formula can use integration along different lines, parallel to the real axis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This theorem implies the Mellin inversion formula for the Laplace transformation, $f(t)={\frac {1}{i2\pi }}\int _{b-i\infty }^{b+i\infty }F(s)e^{st}\,ds$ for any *b* > *a*, where *F*(*s*) is the Laplace transform of *f*(*t*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The hypotheses can be weakened, as in standard Fourier inversion results, to *f*(*t*) *e*−*at* being *L*1, provided that f be of bounded variation in a closed neighborhood of t (cf.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Dini test), the value of f at t be taken to be the arithmetic mean of the left and right limits, and that the integrals be taken in the sense of Cauchy principal values.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform can be defined in any arbitrary number of dimensions n.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] As with the one-dimensional case, there are many conventions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Alternatively, **ξ** can be viewed as belonging to the dual vector space ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n\star }$ ⁠, in which case the dot product becomes the contraction of **x** and **ξ**, usually written as ⟨**x**, **ξ**⟩.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] All of the basic properties listed above hold for the n-dimensional Fourier transform, as do Plancherel's and Parseval's theorem.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] When the function is integrable, the Fourier transform is still uniformly continuous and the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma holds.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Generally speaking, the more concentrated *f*(*x*) is, the more spread out its Fourier transform *f̂*(*ξ*) must be.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In particular, the scaling property of the Fourier transform may be seen as saying: if we squeeze a function in x, its Fourier transform stretches out in ξ.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] It is not possible to arbitrarily concentrate both a function and its Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Suppose *f*(*x*) is an integrable and square-integrable function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] It follows from the Plancherel theorem that *f̂*(*ξ*) is also normalized.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In probability terms, this is the second moment of |*f*(*x*)|2 about zero.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In other words, where f is a (normalized) Gaussian function with variance *σ*2/2π, centered at zero, and its Fourier transform is a Gaussian function with variance *σ*−2/2π.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Gaussian functions are examples of Schwartz functions (see the discussion on tempered distributions below).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] With this constant properly taken into account, the inequality above becomes the statement of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The equality is attained for a Gaussian, as in the previous case.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Fourier's original formulation of the transform did not use complex numbers, but rather sines and cosines.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Statisticians and others still use this form.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This is called an expansion as a trigonometric integral, or a Fourier integral expansion.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Older literature refers to the two transform functions, the Fourier cosine transform, a, and the Fourier sine transform, b.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The function f can be recovered from the sine and cosine transform using $f(t)=2\int _{0}^{\infty }\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }f(\tau )\cos {\bigl (}2\pi \lambda (\tau -t){\bigr )}\,d\tau \,d\lambda .$ together with trigonometric identities.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This is referred to as Fourier's integral formula.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Let the set of homogeneous harmonic polynomials of degree k on **R***n* be denoted by **A***k*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The set **A***k* consists of the solid spherical harmonics of degree k.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The solid spherical harmonics play a similar role in higher dimensions to the Hermite polynomials in dimension one.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The space *L*2(**R***n*) is then a direct sum of the spaces **H***k* and the Fourier transform maps each space **H***k* to itself and it is possible to characterize the action of the Fourier transform on each space **H***k*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Here *J*(*n* + 2*k* − 2)/2 denotes the Bessel function of the first kind with order ⁠*n* + 2*k* − 2/2⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] When *k* = 0 this gives a useful formula for the Fourier transform of a radial function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This is essentially the Hankel transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Moreover, there is a simple recursion relating the cases *n* + 2 and n allowing to compute, e.g., the three-dimensional Fourier transform of a radial function from the one-dimensional one.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In higher dimensions it becomes interesting to study *restriction problems* for the Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform of an integrable function is continuous and the restriction of this function to any set is defined.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] But for a square-integrable function the Fourier transform could be a general *class* of square integrable functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] As such, the restriction of the Fourier transform of an *L*2(**R***n*) function cannot be defined on sets of measure 0.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] It is still an active area of study to understand restriction problems in *L**p* for 1 < *p* < 2.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] It is possible in some cases to define the restriction of a Fourier transform to a set S, provided S has non-zero curvature.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The case when S is the unit sphere in **R***n* is of particular interest.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In this case the Tomas–Stein restriction theorem states that the restriction of the Fourier transform to the unit sphere in **R***n* is a bounded operator on *L**p* provided 1 ≤ *p* ≤ ⁠2*n* + 2/*n* + 3⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] One notable difference between the Fourier transform in 1 dimension versus higher dimensions concerns the partial sum operator.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Consider an increasing collection of measurable sets *E**R* indexed by *R* ∈ (0, ∞): such as balls of radius R centered at the origin, or cubes of side 2*R*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For *n* = 1 and 1 < *p* < ∞, if one takes *ER* = (−*R*, *R*), then fR converges to f in *L**p* as R tends to infinity, by the boundedness of the Hilbert transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Naively one may hope the same holds true for *n* > 1.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In the case that ER is taken to be a cube with side length R, then convergence still holds.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Another natural candidate is the Euclidean ball *E**R* = {*ξ* : |*ξ*| < *R*}.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In order for this partial sum operator to converge, it is necessary that the multiplier for the unit ball be bounded in *L**p*(**R***n*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For *n* ≥ 2 it is a celebrated theorem of Charles Fefferman that the multiplier for the unit ball is never bounded unless *p* = 2.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In fact, when *p* ≠ 2, this shows that not only may fR fail to converge to f in *L**p*, but for some functions *f* ∈ *L**p*(**R***n*), fR is not even an element of *L**p*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The definition of the Fourier transform naturally extends from $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )$ to ⁠ $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Riemann–Lebesgue lemma shows that if $f\in L^{1}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ then its Fourier transform actually belongs to the space of continuous functions that vanish at infinity, i.e., ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}\in C_{0}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})\subset L^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Similarly to the case of one variable, the Fourier transform can be defined on ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform in $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ is no longer given by an ordinary Lebesgue integral, although it can be computed by an improper integral, i.e., ${\widehat {f}}(\xi )=\lim _{R\to \infty }\int _{|x|\leq R}f(x)e^{-i2\pi \xi \cdot x}\,dx$ where the limit is taken in the *L*2 sense.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For an operator to be unitary it is sufficient to show that it is bijective and preserves the inner product.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier inversion theorem implies that the transform is bijective.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] So the transform preserves the inner product.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For ⁠ $1<p<2$ ⁠, the Fourier transform can be defined on $L^{p}(\mathbb {R} )$ by Riesz–Thorin interpolation, which amounts to decomposing such functions into a fat tail part $|f|\leq 1$ in *L*2 plus a fat body part $|f|>1$ in *L*1.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In each of these spaces, the Fourier transform of a function in *L**p*(**R***n*) is in *L**q*(**R***n*), where *q* = ⁠*p*/*p* − 1⁠ is the Hölder conjugate of p (by the Hausdorff–Young inequality).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] However, except for *p* = 2, the image is not easily characterized.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Further extensions become more technical.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform of functions in *L**p* for the range 2 < *p* < ∞ requires the study of distributions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In fact, it can be shown that there are functions in *L**p* with *p* > 2 so that the Fourier transform is not defined as a function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] One might consider enlarging the domain of the Fourier transform from $L^{1}+L^{2}$ by considering generalized functions, or distributions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] A distribution on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is a continuous linear functional on the space $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ of compactly supported smooth functions (i.e. bump functions), equipped with a suitable topology.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Since $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ is dense in ⁠ $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠, the Plancherel theorem allows one to extend the definition of the Fourier transform to general functions in $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ by continuity arguments.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The strategy is then to consider the action of the Fourier transform on $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ and pass to distributions by duality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The obstruction to doing this is that the Fourier transform does not map $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ to ⁠ $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In fact the Fourier transform of an element in $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ can not vanish on an open set; see the above discussion on the uncertainty principle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform can also be defined for tempered distributions ⁠ ${\mathcal {S}}'(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠, dual to the space of Schwartz functions ⁠ ${\mathcal {S}}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The tempered distributions include well-behaved functions of polynomial growth, distributions of compact support as well as all the integrable functions mentioned above.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For the definition of the Fourier transform of a tempered distribution, let f and g be integrable functions, and let ${\widehat {f}}$ and ${\widehat {g}}$ be their Fourier transforms respectively.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Distributions can be differentiated and the above-mentioned compatibility of the Fourier transform with differentiation and convolution remains true for tempered distributions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] If $\mu$ is the probability distribution of a random variable X then its Fourier–Stieltjes transform is, by definition, a characteristic function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] If, in addition, the probability distribution has a probability density function, this definition is subject to the usual Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Stated more generally, when $\mu$ is absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue measure, i.e., $d\mu =f(x)\,dx,$ then ${\widehat {\mu }}(\xi )={\widehat {f}}(\xi ),$ and the Fourier-Stieltjes transform reduces to the usual definition of the Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] That is, the notable difference with the Fourier transform of integrable functions is that the Fourier-Stieltjes transform need not vanish at infinity, i.e., the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma fails for measures.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Bochner's theorem characterizes which functions may arise as the Fourier–Stieltjes transform of a positive measure on the circle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] One example of a finite Borel measure that is not a function is the Dirac measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Its Fourier transform is a constant function (whose value depends on the form of the Fourier transform used).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform may be generalized to any locally compact abelian group, i.e., an abelian group that is also a locally compact Hausdorff space such that the group operation is continuous.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] If G is a locally compact abelian group, it has a translation invariant measure μ, called Haar measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For a locally compact abelian group G, the set of irreducible, i.e. one-dimensional, unitary representations are called its characters.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Riemann–Lebesgue lemma holds in this case; *f̂*(*ξ*) is a function vanishing at infinity on Ĝ.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform on T = R/Z is an example; here T is a locally compact abelian group, and the Haar measure μ on T can be thought of as the Lebesgue measure on [0,1).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Consider a representation of T on the complex plane C thought of as a 1-dimensional complex vector space.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] There is a group of such representations (which are irreducible since C is 1-dim) $\{e_{k}:T\rightarrow GL_{1}(C)=C^{*}\mid k\in Z\}$ where $e_{k}(x)=e^{i2\pi kx}$ for ⁠ $x\in T$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The character of such representation, that is the trace of $e_{k}(x)$ (thought of as a one-by-one matrix) for each $x\in T$ and ⁠ $k\in Z$ ⁠, is $e^{i2\pi kx}$ itself.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The group T is no longer finite but still compact, and it preserves the orthonormality of the character table.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The sequence $\{e_{k}\mid k\in Z\}$ is an orthonormal basis of the space of class functions ⁠ $L^{2}(T,d\mu )$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform is also a special case of the Gelfand transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In this particular context, it is closely related to the Pontryagin duality map defined above.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Given an abelian locally compact Hausdorff topological group G, as before we consider the space *L*1(*G*), defined using a Haar measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] With convolution as multiplication, *L*1(*G*) is an abelian Banach algebra.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Taking the completion with respect to the largest possible *C**-norm gives its enveloping *C**-algebra, called the group *C**-algebra *C**(*G*) of G.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Given any abelian *C**-algebra A, the Gelfand transform gives an isomorphism between A and *C*0(*A*^), where *A*^ is the multiplicative linear functionals, i.e. one-dimensional representations, on A with the weak-* topology.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform can also be defined for functions on a non-abelian group, provided that the group is compact.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Removing the assumption that the underlying group is abelian, irreducible unitary representations need not always be one-dimensional.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This means the Fourier transform on a non-abelian group takes values as Hilbert space operators.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Fourier transform on compact groups is a major tool in representation theory and non-commutative harmonic analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Let G be a compact Hausdorff topological group, and let λ be its normalized Haar measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] Let Σ denote the collection of all isomorphism classes of finite-dimensional irreducible unitary representations, along with a definite choice of representation *U*(*σ*) on the Hilbert space *Hσ* of finite dimension *dσ* for each *σ* ∈ Σ.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The involution on *M*(*G*) is given, for absolutely continuous measures, by $f^{*}(g)={\overline {f(g^{-1})}},$ since compact groups are unimodular.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The Peter–Weyl theorem holds, and a version of the Fourier inversion formula follows: if *f* ∈ *L*2(*G*), then $f(g)=\sum _{\sigma \in \Sigma }d_{\sigma }\operatorname {tr} \left({\widehat {f}}(\sigma )U_{g}^{(\sigma )}\right),$ where the summation is understood as convergent in the *L*2 sense.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The generalization of the Fourier transform to the noncommutative situation has also in part contributed to the development of noncommutative geometry.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] In this context, a categorical generalization of the Fourier transform to noncommutative groups is Tannaka–Krein duality, which replaces the group of characters with the category of representations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] However, this is no longer simply a transform of scalar-valued functions into scalar-valued functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] This limits the usefulness of the Fourier transform for analyzing signals that are localized in time, notably transients, or any signal of finite extent.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] As alternatives to the Fourier transform, in time–frequency analysis, one uses time–frequency transforms or time–frequency distributions to represent signals in a form that has some time information and some frequency information – by the uncertainty principle, there is a trade-off between these.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The following figures provide a visual illustration of how the Fourier transform's integral measures whether a frequency is present in a particular function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The first image depicts the function ⁠ $f(t)=\cos(2\pi \ 3t)\ e^{-\pi t^{2}}$ ⁠, which is a 3 Hz cosine wave (the first term) shaped by a Gaussian envelope function (the second term) that smoothly turns the wave on and off.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The next 2 images show the product ⁠ $f(t)e^{-i2\pi 3t}$ ⁠, which must be integrated to calculate the Fourier transform at +3 Hz.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The real part of the integrand has a non-negative average value, because the alternating signs of $f(t)$ and $\operatorname {Re} (e^{-i2\pi 3t})$ oscillate at the same rate and in phase, whereas $f(t)$ and $\operatorname {Im} (e^{-i2\pi 3t})$ oscillate at the same rate but with orthogonal phase.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The absolute value of the Fourier transform at +3 Hz is 0.5, which is relatively large.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] When added to the Fourier transform at -3 Hz (which is identical because we started with a real signal), we find that the amplitude of the 3 Hz frequency component is 1.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] However, when you try to measure a frequency that is not present, both the real and imaginary component of the integral vary rapidly between positive and negative values.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] For instance, the red curve is looking for 5 Hz.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The absolute value of its integral is nearly zero, indicating that almost no 5 Hz component was in the signal.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] The general situation is usually more complicated than this, but heuristically this is how the Fourier transform measures how much of an individual frequency is present in a function ⁠ $f(t)$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p02] To re-enforce an earlier point, the reason for the response at $\xi =-3$ Hz is because $\cos(2\pi 3t)$ and $\cos(2\pi (-3)t)$ are indistinguishable.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Linear operations performed in one domain (time or frequency) have corresponding operations in the other domain, which are sometimes easier to perform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The operation of differentiation in the time domain corresponds to multiplication by the frequency, so some differential equations are easier to analyze in the frequency domain.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Also, convolution in the time domain corresponds to ordinary multiplication in the frequency domain (see *Convolution theorem*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] After performing the desired operations, transformation of the result can be made back to the time domain.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Harmonic analysis is the systematic study of the relationship between the frequency and time domains, including the kinds of functions or operations that are "simpler" in one or the other, and has deep connections to many areas of modern mathematics.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Perhaps the most important use of the Fourier transformation is to solve partial differential equations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Many of the equations of the mathematical physics of the nineteenth century can be treated this way.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] As usual, the problem is not to find a solution: there are infinitely many.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For the heat equation, only one boundary condition can be required (usually the first one).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But for the wave equation, there are still infinitely many solutions y that satisfy the first boundary condition.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But when one imposes both conditions, there is only one possible solution.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] It is easier to find the Fourier transform ŷ of the solution than to find the solution directly.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] After ŷ is determined, we can apply the inverse Fourier transformation to find y.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] First, note that any function of the forms $\cos {\bigl (}2\pi \xi (x\pm t){\bigr )}{\text{ or }}\sin {\bigl (}2\pi \xi (x\pm t){\bigr )}$ satisfies the wave equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] These are called the elementary solutions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This integral may be interpreted as a continuous linear combination of solutions for the linear equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Now this resembles the formula for the Fourier synthesis of a function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In fact, this is the real inverse Fourier transform of *a*± and *b*± in the variable x.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The third step is to examine how to find the specific unknown coefficient functions *a*± and *b*± that will lead to y satisfying the boundary conditions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] We are interested in the values of these solutions at *t* = 0.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] These are four linear equations for the four unknowns *a*± and *b*±, in terms of the Fourier sine and cosine transforms of the boundary conditions, which are easily solved by elementary algebra, provided that these transforms can be found.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In summary, we chose a set of elementary solutions, parametrized by ξ, of which the general solution would be a (continuous) linear combination in the form of an integral over the parameter ξ.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But this integral was in the form of a Fourier integral.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The next step was to express the boundary conditions in terms of these integrals, and set them equal to the given functions f and g.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But these expressions also took the form of a Fourier integral because of the properties of the Fourier transform of a derivative.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The last step was to exploit Fourier inversion by applying the Fourier transformation to both sides, thus obtaining expressions for the coefficient functions *a*± and *b*± in terms of the given boundary conditions f and g.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] From a higher point of view, Fourier's procedure can be reformulated more conceptually.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Since there are two variables, we will use the Fourier transformation in both x and t rather than operate as Fourier did, who only transformed in the spatial variables.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Note that ŷ must be considered in the sense of a distribution since *y*(*x*, *t*) is not going to be *L*1: as a wave, it will persist through time and thus is not a transient phenomenon.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But it will be bounded and so its Fourier transform can be defined as a distribution.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The operational properties of the Fourier transformation that are relevant to this equation are that it takes differentiation in x to multiplication by *i*2π*ξ* and differentiation with respect to t to multiplication by *i*2π*f* where f is the frequency.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Then the wave equation becomes an algebraic equation in ŷ: $\xi ^{2}{\widehat {y}}(\xi ,f)=f^{2}{\widehat {y}}(\xi ,f).$ This is equivalent to requiring *ŷ*(*ξ*, *f*) = 0 unless *ξ* = ±*f*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Right away, this explains why the choice of elementary solutions we made earlier worked so well: obviously *ŷ* = *δ*(*ξ* ± *f*) will be solutions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Applying Fourier inversion to these delta functions, we obtain the elementary solutions we picked earlier.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] But from the higher point of view, one does not pick elementary solutions, but rather considers the space of all distributions that are supported on the (degenerate) conic *ξ*2 − *f*2 = 0.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Now, as before, applying the one-variable Fourier transformation in the variable x to these functions of x yields two equations in the two unknown distributions *s*± (which can be taken to be ordinary functions if the boundary conditions are *L*1 or *L*2).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] From a calculational point of view, the drawback of course is that one must first calculate the Fourier transforms of the boundary conditions, then assemble the solution from these, and then calculate an inverse Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Closed form formulas are rare, except when there is some geometric symmetry that can be exploited, and the numerical calculations are difficult because of the oscillatory nature of the integrals, which makes convergence slow and hard to estimate.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For practical calculations, other methods are often used.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The twentieth century has seen application of these methods to all linear partial differential equations with polynomial coefficients as well as an extension to certain classes of nonlinear partial differential equations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Specifically, nonlinear evolution equations (i.e. those equations that describe how a particular quantity evolves in time from a specified initial state) that can be associated with linear eigenvalue problems whose eigenvalues are integrals of the nonlinear equations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] As it may be considered an extension of Fourier analysis to nonlinear problems, the solution method is called the **nonlinear Fourier transform** (or **inverse scattering transform**) method.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is also used in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) and in other kinds of spectroscopy, e.g. infrared (FTIR).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In NMR an exponentially shaped free induction decay (FID) signal is acquired in the time domain and Fourier-transformed to a Lorentzian line-shape in the frequency domain.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is also used in magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and mass spectrometry.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is useful in quantum mechanics in at least two different ways.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] To begin with, the basic conceptual structure of quantum mechanics postulates the existence of pairs of complementary variables, connected by the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For example, in one dimension, the spatial variable q of, say, a particle, can only be measured by the quantum mechanical "position operator" at the cost of losing information about the momentum p of the particle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Therefore, the physical state of the particle can either be described by a function, called "the wave function", of q or by a function of p but not by a function of both variables.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The variable p is called the conjugate variable to q.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In classical mechanics, the physical state of a particle (existing in one dimension, for simplicity of exposition) would be given by assigning definite values to both p and q simultaneously.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Thus, the set of all possible physical states is the two-dimensional real vector space with a p-axis and a q-axis called the phase space.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In contrast, quantum mechanics chooses a polarisation of this space in the sense that it picks a subspace of one-half the dimension, for example, the q-axis alone, but instead of considering only points, takes the set of all complex-valued "wave functions" on this axis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Nevertheless, choosing the p-axis is an equally valid polarisation, yielding a different representation of the set of possible physical states of the particle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Physically realisable states are *L*2, and so by the Plancherel theorem, their Fourier transforms are also *L*2.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Therefore, the Fourier transform can be used to pass from one way of representing the state of the particle, by a wave function of position, to another way of representing the state of the particle: by a wave function of momentum.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Infinitely many different polarisations are possible, and all are equally valid.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Being able to transform states from one representation to another by the Fourier transform is not only convenient but also the underlying reason of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The other use of the Fourier transform in both quantum mechanics and quantum field theory is to solve the applicable wave equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This is the same as the heat equation except for the presence of the imaginary unit i.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Fourier methods can be used to solve this equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The "elementary solutions", as we referred to them above, are the so-called "stationary states" of the particle, and Fourier's algorithm, as described above, can still be used to solve the boundary value problem of the future evolution of ψ given its values for *t* = 0.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Neither of these approaches is of much practical use in quantum mechanics.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Boundary value problems and the time-evolution of the wave function is not of much practical interest: it is the stationary states that are most important.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In relativistic quantum mechanics, the Schrödinger equation becomes a wave equation as was usual in classical physics, except that complex-valued waves are considered.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This is, from the mathematical point of view, the same as the wave equation of classical physics solved above (but with a complex-valued wave, which makes no difference in the methods).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This is of great use in quantum field theory: each separate Fourier component of a wave can be treated as a separate harmonic oscillator and then quantized, a procedure known as "second quantization".
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Fourier methods have been adapted to also deal with non-trivial interactions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Finally, the number operator of the quantum harmonic oscillator can be interpreted, for example via the Mehler kernel, as the generator of the Fourier transform ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform is used for the spectral analysis of time-series.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The subject of statistical signal processing does not, however, usually apply the Fourier transformation to the signal itself.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Even if a real signal is indeed transient, it has been found in practice advisable to model a signal by a function (or, alternatively, a stochastic process) that is stationary in the sense that its characteristic properties are constant over all time.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform of such a function does not exist in the usual sense, and it has been found more useful for the analysis of signals to instead take the Fourier transform of its autocorrelation function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This function is a function of the time-lag τ elapsing between the values of f to be correlated.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For most functions f that occur in practice, R is a bounded even function of the time-lag τ and for typical noisy signals it turns out to be uniformly continuous with a maximum at *τ* = 0.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The autocorrelation function, more properly called the autocovariance function unless it is normalized in some appropriate fashion, measures the strength of the correlation between the values of f separated by a time lag.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This is a way of searching for the correlation of f with its own past.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] It is useful even for other statistical tasks besides the analysis of signals.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For example, if *f*(*t*) represents the temperature at time t, one expects a strong correlation with the temperature at a time lag of 24 hours.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This Fourier transform is called the power spectral density function of f.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The power spectrum, as indicated by this density function P, measures the amount of variance contributed to the data by the frequency ξ.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In electrical signals, the variance is proportional to the average power (energy per unit time), and so the power spectrum describes how much the different frequencies contribute to the average power of the signal.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This process is called the spectral analysis of time-series and is analogous to the usual analysis of variance of data that is not a time-series (ANOVA).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Knowledge of which frequencies are "important" in this sense is crucial for the proper design of filters and for the proper evaluation of measuring apparatuses.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] It can also be useful for the scientific analysis of the phenomena responsible for producing the data.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The power spectrum of a signal can also be approximately measured directly by measuring the average power that remains in a signal after all the frequencies outside a narrow band have been filtered out.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Spectral analysis is carried out for visual signals as well.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The power spectrum ignores all phase relations, which is good enough for many purposes, but for video signals other types of spectral analysis must also be employed, still using the Fourier transform as a tool.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] A disadvantage of the capital letter notation is when expressing a transform such as ${\widehat {f}}\cdot g$ or ⁠ ${\widehat {f}}'$ ⁠, which become the more awkward ${\mathcal {F}}\{f\cdot g\}$ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {F}}\{f'\}$ ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Although tildes may be used as in ${\tilde {f}}$ to indicate Fourier transforms, tildes may also be used to indicate a modification of a quantity with a more Lorentz invariant form, such as ⁠ ${\tilde {dk}}={\frac {dk}{(2\pi )^{3}2\omega }}$ ⁠, so care must be taken.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Similarly, ${\widehat {f}}$ often denotes the Hilbert transform of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Then the inverse transform can be written: $f(x)=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }A(\xi )\ e^{i{\bigl (}2\pi \xi x+\varphi (\xi ){\bigr )}}\,d\xi ,$ which is a recombination of all the frequency components of *f*(*x*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Each component is a complex sinusoid of the form *e*2π*ixξ* whose amplitude is *A*(*ξ*) and whose initial phase angle (at *x* = 0) is *φ*(*ξ*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The Fourier transform may be thought of as a mapping on function spaces.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This mapping is here denoted F and F(*f*) is used to denote the Fourier transform of the function f.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This mapping is linear, which means that F can also be seen as a linear transformation on the function space and implies that the standard notation in linear algebra of applying a linear transformation to a vector (here the function *f*) can be used to write F *f* instead of F(*f*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Since the result of applying the Fourier transform is again a function, we can be interested in the value of this function evaluated at the value ξ for its variable, and this is denoted either as F *f*(*ξ*) or as (F *f*)(*ξ*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Notice that in the former case, it is implicitly understood that F is applied first to f and then the resulting function is evaluated at ξ, not the other way around.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In mathematics and various applied sciences, it is often necessary to distinguish between a function f and the value of f when its variable equals x, denoted *f*(*x*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] This means that a notation like F(*f*(*x*)) formally can be interpreted as the Fourier transform of the values of f at x.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Despite this flaw, the previous notation appears frequently, often when a particular function or a function of a particular variable is to be transformed.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Notice, that the last example is only correct under the assumption that the transformed function is a function of x, not of *x*0.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] As discussed above, the characteristic function of a random variable is the same as the Fourier–Stieltjes transform of its distribution measure, but in this context it is typical to take a different convention for the constants.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] As in the case of the "non-unitary angular frequency" convention above, the factor of 2π appears in neither the normalizing constant nor the exponent.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Unlike any of the conventions appearing above, this convention takes the opposite sign in the exponent.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The appropriate computation method largely depends how the original mathematical function is represented and the desired form of the output function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] In this section we consider both functions of a continuous variable, ⁠ $f(x)$ ⁠, and functions of a discrete variable (i.e. ordered pairs of x and f values).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] For discrete-valued ⁠ x ⁠, the transform integral becomes a summation of sinusoids, which is still a continuous function of frequency (⁠ $\xi$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] When the sinusoids are harmonically related (i.e. when the x -values are spaced at integer multiples of an interval), the transform is called discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Sampling the DTFT at equally-spaced values of frequency is the most common modern method of computation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Efficient procedures, depending on the frequency resolution needed, are described at Discrete-time Fourier transform § Sampling the DTFT.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The discrete Fourier transform (DFT), used there, is usually computed by a fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] When mathematically possible, this provides a transform for a continuum of frequency values.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] Discrete sampling of the Fourier transform can also be done by numerical integration of the definition at each value of frequency for which transform is desired.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The numerical integration approach works on a much broader class of functions than the analytic approach.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] If the input function is a series of ordered pairs, numerical integration reduces to just a summation over the set of data pairs.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p03] The DTFT is a common subcase of this more general situation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] The following tables record some closed-form Fourier transforms.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] For functions *f*(*x*) and *g*(*x*) denote their Fourier transforms by *f̂* and *ĝ*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] Only the three most common conventions are included.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] It may be useful to notice that entry 105 gives a relationship between the Fourier transform of a function and the original function, which can be seen as relating the Fourier transform and its inverse.
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] The Fourier transforms in this table may be found in Erdélyi (1954) or Kammler (2000, appendix).
[src:harmonic-analysis/fourier-transform-p04] The Fourier transforms in this table may be found in Campbell & Foster (1948), Erdélyi (1954), or Kammler (2000, appendix).
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] A related tradition is **abstract harmonic analysis** where the emphasis is on functions and representations on topological groups, including Pontryagin duality, the Peter–Weyl theorem, and Plancherel-type theorems.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis overlaps substantially with Fourier analysis, real analysis, functional analysis, partial differential equations, potential theory, ergodic theory, representation theory, and number theory.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis shares many methods with Fourier analysis, which is also concerned with the decomposition of functions into frequencies or harmonics.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] It differs from Fourier analysis chiefly in the kinds of functions considered and the types of questions addressed.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Fourier analysis has a basic form in Hilbert space, where orthogonality and Plancherel's theorem are central, and studies objects close to the orthogonal frequency decomposition, such as multipliers and convolutions and linear constant-coefficient partial differential equations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] In contrast, harmonic analysis often studies Fourier-like decompositions in situations where orthogonality alone is not enough.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] As a result, it often must look for finer kinds of decompositions and properties of functions than those of Fourier theory.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] One source of harmonic analysis, and especially of its real-variable tradition, is the study of harmonic functions and classical potential theory.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] In particular, the Poisson integral formula represents a harmonic function in a disk or half-space in terms of boundary data.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] But the boundary behavior of harmonic functions, and of the Poisson kernel, is often more delicate than Fourier methods alone can resolve.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Thus questions about the convergence of Poisson integrals, the existence of boundary values, and the behavior of conjugate harmonic functions lead to maximal estimates and singular integral operators.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Modern harmonic analysis is usually concerned with real variable methods first encountered the study of harmonic functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The Poisson integral sits between real and complex methods: complex analysis gives powerful tools for holomorphic and harmonic functions, while boundary convergence and estimates in *L**p*, weak *L*1, and related spaces often require real-variable methods.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The real variable theory is also apparent in the related Hilbert transform, which arises in the theory of conjugate harmonic functions and boundary values of holomorphic functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] These transforms became a prototype for more general singular integral operators, which the real variable methods of harmonic analysis are more suited for.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] In higher dimensions, analogous operators include the Riesz transforms, which are connected with the derivatives of harmonic and Newtonian potentials.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] One ingredient is Hardy–Littlewood maximal function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Maximal functions are used to control pointwise convergence, differentiation of integrals, and boundary limits of harmonic or subharmonic functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] They also provide a model for many later estimates in real-variable analysis, including weak-type inequalities, interpolation arguments, and weighted norm inequalities.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The theory of Calderón–Zygmund operators is one of the main developments in the analytic treatment of singular integral operators.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] This theory gives conditions under which singular integral operators are bounded on spaces such as *L**p* and related function spaces.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] It handles the Hilbert transform, Riesz transforms, many convolution operators, and singular integral operators arising in elliptic and parabolic partial differential equations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Littlewood–Paley theory is another component of harmonic analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] It seeks to decompose functions by scale or frequency and estimating square functions built from the resulting pieces.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] This technique is used together with Fourier theory, but replaces the orthogonality arguments of Fourier theory with almost-orthogonality methods that are suited to situations where orthogonality is no longer available, such as $L^{p}$ where $p\neq 2$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The kind of decompositions involved are often finer than the Hilbert-space methods that suffice for many basic questions in Fourier analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The Fourier transform remains a fundamental tool in harmonic analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] But much of modern real-variable harmonic analysis is concerned less with explicit Fourier inversion than with estimates for operators.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] This distinguishes it from classical Fourier analysis and also from abstract harmonic analysis, where the emphasis is on symmetry, locally compact groups, and representation theory.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] A real-variable method in harmonic analysis is to decompose a function into a controlled part and a collection of localized exceptional parts.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] One example is the Calderón–Zygmund decomposition.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Given an integrable function f and a threshold $\lambda >0$ , one selects intervals or cubes on which the average size of f is larger than $\lambda$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Here g is the "good" part: it agrees with f away from the selected cubes and is bounded in size by a constant multiple of $\lambda$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The cubes occupy a set whose total measure is controlled by $\|f\|_{1}/\lambda$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Thus the places where f is too large are localized, while the remaining part is bounded and easier to estimate.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] To estimate an operator such as a singular integral, one treats g using Hilbert-space or $L^{2}$ estimates, where orthogonality and boundedness are available.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The localized terms $b_{j}$ are handled separately: near their supporting cubes, the total measure is small, while far from those cubes their mean-zero cancellation reduces the size of the operator.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] In this way a function is split locally according to size, before it is decomposed globally into frequencies.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] This local-global decomposition is characteristic of many arguments in harmonic analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] For example, the Hilbert transform is not bounded in $L^{1}$ , but it does map into weak-type $L^{1,\infty }$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] A proof takes a function $f\in L^{1}\cap L^{2}$ and decomposes it into a $\lambda$ -bounded part plus a $2\lambda$ mean-bounded part over a collection of subintervals, $f=g+b$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The Hilbert transform is bounded on $L^{2}$ , so the good part g inherits the same bound.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Fourier restriction problems illustrate another way in which harmonic analysis extends classical Fourier analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] In elementary Fourier analysis, the Fourier transform is first studied as a transform on functions on a whole space, such as $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , with basic results concerning inversion, convolution, Plancherel's theorem, and the decomposition of functions into frequencies.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] A restriction problem asks the question of whether the Fourier transform of a function can be meaningfully restricted to a lower-dimensional set in frequency space, such as a sphere, cone, or paraboloid.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] If $f\in L^{1}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ , then ${\widehat {f}}$ is continuous, so its restriction to a smooth surface S is well defined.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The problem becomes nontrivial for functions in $L^{p}(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ , where the Fourier transform need not be given by an ordinary pointwise-defined function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] can hold, where $d\sigma$ is surface measure on S .
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] In this formulation, $Eg$ is a superposition of plane waves whose frequencies lie on the surface S .
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The Fourier-analytic aspect of the problem is the oscillatory representation itself.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] A function is described by waves with prescribed frequencies, and different choices of S correspond to different geometric or physical situations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] For example, the paraboloid is connected with the free Schrödinger equation, while the cone is connected with the wave equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The harmonic-analytic aspect is the estimate theory, determining which exponents are possible and how the answer depends on curvature, cancellation, scaling, and the way wave packets overlap in physical space.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Frequencies concentrated on a flat hyperplane do not disperse like frequencies on a curved hypersurface.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] For curved surfaces, oscillation can force cancellation and spreading, allowing estimates that would fail for flat sets.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] A basic result of this type is the Stein–Tomas theorem, which gives an $L^{2}$ restriction theorem for the sphere.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] More advanced restriction problems involve bilinear and multilinear estimates, wave-packet decompositions, induction on scales, and connections with Kakeya-type geometry.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Thus in Fourier restriction problems, Fourier analysis supplies the transform and the frequency-space formulation, while harmonic analysis studies the resulting inequalities and the fine behavior of the associated operators.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis supplies analytic tools for results relating to the Lebesgue measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] One is the Lebesgue differentiation theorem, which states that a locally integrable function is almost everywhere equal to the limit of its average over balls.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The proof uses weak-type estimates and maximal functions to control the almost everywhere convergence.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis is used in classical results of ergodic theory.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The maximal ergodic theorem is analogous to the Hardy–Littlewood maximal theorem: it bounds the measure of the set on which a supremum of ergodic averages is large.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Such maximal estimates are used in proofs of the Birkhoff ergodic theorem, where they help pass from convergence on a dense class of functions to almost-everywhere convergence.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Calderón showed that harmonic analytic estimates for translation-invariant operators can be transferred to ergodic averages associated with measure-preserving transformations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] This allows harmonic-analytic estimates for maximal functions and singular integrals to be used in ergodic settings.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Later work on ergodic averages has focused on studying the oscillation and deviations around those averages.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] This involves estimating short variations in $L^{p}$ norms, using techniques of harmonic analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis is closely connected with Sobolev spaces and the regularity theory of partial differential equations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Riesz potentials and fractional integral operators are used to prove Sobolev-type inequalities, including embeddings between *L**p* spaces and spaces of weakly differentiable functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Singular integral estimates also give information about weak derivatives.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] For example, Calderón–Zygmund operators are used to obtain *L**p* estimates for derivatives of solutions to elliptic equations from estimates on the equation itself.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] In this way, harmonic-analytic bounds for singular integrals become regularity estimates for solutions of differential equations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Littlewood–Paley theory gives another description of Sobolev and related function spaces by decomposing functions into pieces at different scales or frequencies.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] This point of view is especially useful for fractional Sobolev spaces, Besov spaces, Triebel–Lizorkin spaces, and nonlinear problems where estimates must be made scale by scale.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis is used in a different, but related, sense in mathematics, to describe how real or complex functions (often on very general domains) can be studied using symmetries such as translations or rotations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] An example is the decomposition of a function on Euclidean space into spherical harmonics, which are eigenfunctions of the Laplace operator.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Abstract harmonic analysis extends the classical spherical harmonic decompositions to functions on spaces associated to other groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] In this way, the theory is close to representation theory and functional analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] One of the most modern branches of harmonic analysis, having its roots in the mid-20th century, is analysis on topological groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] The core motivating ideas are the various Fourier transforms, which can be generalized to a transform of functions defined on Hausdorff locally compact topological groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] One of the major results in the theory of functions on abelian locally compact groups is called Pontryagin duality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis studies the properties of that duality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Different generalization of Fourier transforms attempts to extend those features to different settings, for instance, first to the case of general abelian topological groups and second to the case of non-abelian Lie groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis is closely related to the theory of unitary group representations for general non-abelian locally compact groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] For compact groups, the Peter–Weyl theorem explains how one may get harmonics by choosing one irreducible representation out of each equivalence class of representations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] This choice of harmonics enjoys some of the valuable properties of the classical Fourier transform in terms of carrying convolutions to pointwise products or otherwise showing a certain understanding of the underlying group structure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] See also: Non-commutative harmonic analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] If the group is neither abelian nor compact, no general satisfactory theory is currently known ("satisfactory" means at least as strong as the Plancherel theorem).
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] However, many specific cases have been analyzed, for example, SL*n*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] In this case, representations in infinite dimensions play a crucial role.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Abstract harmonic analysis also has applications in number theory.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] In Tate's thesis, questions about L-functions are formulated using harmonic analysis on the adele ring and idele group.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis, in this latter sense, is closely connected with spectral theory, especially through the study of the Laplacian and other differential operators.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] On Euclidean spaces, manifolds, symmetric spaces, and graphs, questions about eigenfunctions, eigenvalues, heat kernels, and wave propagation are often treated using harmonic-analytic methods.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] This point of view includes problems such as hearing the shape of a drum and the analysis of spherical functions on symmetric spaces.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] On Euclidean space, harmonic analysis also studies phenomena special to the Fourier transform on **R***n*, such as rotation invariance, restriction estimates, radial Fourier transforms, Bessel functions, and spherical harmonics.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] These topics connect the real-variable theory with classical special functions and with partial differential equations.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Several more specialized areas use harmonic-analytic methods.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis on symmetric spaces and locally compact groups is related to representation theory.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Harmonic analysis on tube domains is connected with Hardy spaces and several complex variables.
[src:harmonic-analysis/harmonic-analysis] Automorphic forms may also be viewed as harmonic-analytic objects associated with arithmetic symmetry groups, although they are usually treated as a separate subject closely connected with number theory and the Langlands program.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] In mathematics, the **Plancherel theorem** (sometimes called the **Parseval–Plancherel identity**) is a result in harmonic analysis, proven by Michel Plancherel in 1910.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] It is a generalization of Parseval's theorem; often used in the fields of science and engineering, proving the unitarity of the Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] The theorem states that the integral of a function's squared modulus is equal to the integral of the squared modulus of its frequency spectrum.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] This implies that the Fourier transform restricted to $L^{1}(\mathbb {R} )\cap L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ has a unique extension to a linear isometric map $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )\mapsto L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ , sometimes called the Plancherel transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] This isometry is actually a unitary map.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] In effect, this makes it possible to speak of Fourier transforms of *L**2* functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] A proof of the theorem is available from *Rudin (1987, Chapter 9)*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] The basic idea is to prove it for Gaussian distributions, and then use density.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] But a standard Gaussian is transformed to itself under the Fourier transformation, and the theorem is trivial in that case.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] Finally, the standard transformation properties of the Fourier transform then imply Plancherel for all Gaussians.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] Plancherel's theorem remains valid as stated on *n*-dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] The theorem also holds more generally in locally compact abelian groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] There is also a version of the Plancherel theorem which makes sense for non-commutative locally compact groups satisfying certain technical assumptions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] This is the subject of non-commutative harmonic analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] Due to the polarization identity, one can also apply Plancherel's theorem to the $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ inner product of two functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] There is also a Plancherel theorem for the Fourier transform in locally compact groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] In the case of an abelian group G , there is a Pontryagin dual group ${\widehat {G}}$ of characters on G .
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] Given a Haar measure on G , the Fourier transform of a function in $L^{1}(G)$ is ${\hat {f}}(\chi )=\int _{G}{\overline {\chi (g)}}f(g)\,dg$ for $\chi$ a character on G .
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] The Plancherel theorem states that there is a Haar measure on ${\widehat {G}}$ , the *dual measure* such that $\|f\|_{G}^{2}=\|{\hat {f}}\|_{\widehat {G}}^{2}$ for all $f\in L^{1}\cap L^{2}$ (and the Fourier transform is also in $L^{2}$ ).
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] The theorem also holds in many non-abelian locally compact groups, except that the set of irreducible unitary representations ${\widehat {G}}$ may not be a group.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] For example, when G is a finite group, ${\widehat {G}}$ is the set of irreducible characters.
[src:harmonic-analysis/plancherel-theorem] In full generality, a Plancherel theorem is $\|f\|_{G}^{2}=\int _{\hat {G}}\|{\hat {f}}(\rho )\|_{HS}^{2}d\mu (\rho )$ where the norm is the Hilbert-Schmidt norm of the operator ${\hat {f}}(\rho )=\int _{G}f(g)\rho (g)^{*}\,dg$ and the measure $\mu$ , if one exists, is called the Plancherel measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The **Pontryagin dual** of a locally compact abelian group is the locally compact abelian topological group, consisting of the continuous group homomorphisms from the group to the circle group, with the operation of pointwise multiplication and the topology of uniform convergence on compact sets.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The **Pontryagin duality theorem** establishes Pontryagin duality by stating that any locally compact abelian group is naturally isomorphic with its bidual (the dual of its dual).
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The Fourier inversion theorem is a special case of this theorem.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The subject is named after Lev Pontryagin, who laid down the foundations for the theory of locally compact abelian groups and their duality during his early mathematical works in 1934.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Pontryagin's treatment relied on the groups being second-countable and either compact or discrete.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This was improved to cover the general locally compact abelian groups by Egbert van Kampen in 1935 and André Weil in 1940.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The theory, introduced by Lev Pontryagin and combined with the Haar measure introduced by John von Neumann, André Weil and others depends on the theory of the dual group of a locally compact abelian group.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Similarly, a group G and its dual group ${\widehat {G}}$ are not in general isomorphic, but their endomorphism rings are opposite to each other: ${\text{End}}(G)\cong {\text{End}}({\widehat {G}})^{\text{op}}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] More categorically, this is not just an isomorphism of endomorphism algebras, but a contravariant equivalence of categories – see *§ Categorical considerations*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] A topological group is a locally compact group if the underlying topological space is locally compact and Hausdorff; a topological group is *abelian* if the underlying group is abelian.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] For a locally compact abelian group G , the **Pontryagin dual** is the group ${\widehat {G}}$ of continuous group homomorphisms from G to the circle group T .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] That is, ${\widehat {G}}:=\operatorname {Hom} (G,T).$ The Pontryagin dual ${\widehat {G}}$ is usually endowed with the topology given by uniform convergence on compact sets (that is, the topology induced by the compact-open topology on the space of all continuous functions from G to T ).
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Before 1938, several developments contributed to what became known as **Pontryagin duality**.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Pavel Alexandrov (late 1920s) developed the theory of inverse systems (projective limits) in topology, including so-called projection spectra.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] While not directly part of duality theory for topological groups, these methods introduced systematic use of limiting processes that later became important in the study of non-finitely generated groups and duality phenomena.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Alfréd Haar (1933) introduced Haar measure in *Der Maßbegriff in der Theorie der kontinuierlichen Gruppen*, providing a translation-invariant integration theory on locally compact groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This became a fundamental tool for harmonic analysis and for the later formulation of Pontryagin duality in full generality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Raymond Paley and Norbert Wiener (1933–1934), in work culminating in *Fourier Transforms in the Complex Domain* (1934), systematically studied Fourier transforms and characters of abelian groups (primarily discrete or Euclidean).
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] They emphasized a duality between a group and its character group, though their framework did not yet extend to general locally compact abelian groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] James Waddell Alexander II (1934–1935) clarified duality phenomena in algebraic topology and introduced early cohomological ideas, notably in *On the Chains of a Complex and Their Duals*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] While not directly part of Pontryagin duality, this work contributed to the broader mathematical notion of duality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] John von Neumann (1934) studied almost periodic functions on groups and extended harmonic analysis beyond countable settings, removing certain separability assumptions and anticipating the need for a general locally compact framework.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Egbert van Kampen (1935), in *Locally Bicompact Abelian Groups and Their Character Groups*, refined the topology on character groups and removed countability restrictions, bringing the theory close to its modern formulation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Claude Chevalley (1936) applied duality ideas in class field theory, demonstrating their arithmetic significance.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] These results were soon extended to all locally compact abelian groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Canonical means that there is a naturally defined map $\operatorname {ev} _{G}\colon G\to {\widehat {\widehat {G}}}$ ; more importantly, the map should be functorial in G .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] In other words, each group element x is identified to the evaluation character on the dual.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This is strongly analogous to the canonical isomorphism between a finite-dimensional vector space and its double dual, $V\cong V^{**}$ , and it is worth mentioning that any vector space V is an abelian group.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] If G is a finite abelian group, then $G\cong {\widehat {G}}$ but this isomorphism is not canonical.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Making this statement precise (in general) requires thinking about dualizing not only on groups, but also on maps between the groups, in order to treat dualization as a functor and prove the identity functor and the dualization functor are not naturally equivalent.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Also the duality theorem implies that for any group (not necessarily finite) the dualization functor is an exact functor.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] One of the most remarkable facts about a locally compact group G is that it carries an essentially unique natural measure, the Haar measure, which allows one to consistently measure the "size" of sufficiently regular subsets of G .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] "Sufficiently regular subset" here means a Borel set; that is, an element of the σ-algebra generated by the compact sets.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Except for positive scaling factors, a Haar measure on G is unique.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The Haar measure on G allows us to define the notion of integral for (complex-valued) Borel functions defined on the group.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] In particular, one may consider various *Lp* spaces associated to the Haar measure $\mu$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Note that, since any two Haar measures on G are equal up to a scaling factor, this $L^{p}$ -space is independent of the choice of Haar measure and thus perhaps could be written as $L^{p}(G)$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] However, the $L^{p}$ -norm on this space depends on the choice of Haar measure, so if one wants to talk about isometries it is important to keep track of the Haar measure being used.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The dual group of a locally compact abelian group is used as the underlying space for an abstract version of the Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] If $f\in L^{1}(G)$ , then the Fourier transform is the function ${\widehat {f}}$ on ${\widehat {G}}$ defined by ${\widehat {f}}(\chi )=\int _{G}f(x){\overline {\chi (x)}}\ d\mu (x),$ where the integral is relative to Haar measure $\mu$ on G .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This is also denoted $({\mathcal {F}}f)(\chi )$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Note the Fourier transform depends on the choice of Haar measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] It is not too difficult to show that the Fourier transform of an $L^{1}$ function on G is a bounded continuous function on ${\widehat {G}}$ which vanishes at infinity.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The *inverse Fourier transform* of an integrable function on ${\widehat {G}}$ is given by ${\check {g}}(x)=\int _{\widehat {G}}g(\chi )\chi (x)\ d\nu (\chi ),$ where the integral is relative to the Haar measure $\nu$ on the dual group ${\widehat {G}}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The measure $\nu$ on ${\widehat {G}}$ that appears in the Fourier inversion formula is called the dual measure to $\mu$ and may be denoted ${\widehat {\mu }}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] However, if we change the way we identify $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with its dual group, by using the pairing $(\mathbf {v} ,\mathbf {w} )\mapsto e^{2\pi i\mathbf {v} \cdot \mathbf {w} },$ then Lebesgue measure on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is equal to its own dual measure.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This convention minimizes the number of factors of $2\pi$ that show up in various places when computing Fourier transforms or inverse Fourier transforms on Euclidean space.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] But using the pairing, which keeps the pre-factor as unity, $(\mathbf {v} ,\mathbf {w} )\mapsto e^{2\pi i\mathbf {v} \cdot \mathbf {w} }$ makes $e^{-\pi x^{2}}$ self-dual instead.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This second definition for the Fourier transform has the advantage that it maps the multiplicative identity to the convolution identity, which is useful as $L^{1}$ is a convolution algebra.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] See the next section on the group algebra.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] In addition, this form is also necessarily isometric on $L^{2}$ spaces.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] See below at Plancherel and *L*2 Fourier inversion theorems.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This algebra is referred to as the *Group Algebra* of G .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] By the Fubini–Tonelli theorem, the convolution is submultiplicative with respect to the $L^{1}$ norm, making $L^{1}(G)$ a Banach algebra.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The Banach algebra $L^{1}(G)$ has a multiplicative identity element if and only if G is a discrete group, namely the function that is 1 at the identity and zero elsewhere.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] It is an important property of the group algebra that these exhaust the set of non-trivial (that is, not identically zero) multiplicative linear functionals on the group algebra; see section 34 of Loomis (1953).
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This means the Fourier transform is a special case of the Gelfand transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] As we have stated, the dual group of a locally compact abelian group is a locally compact abelian group in its own right and thus has a Haar measure, or more precisely a whole family of scale-related Haar measures.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Note that for non-compact locally compact groups G the space $L^{1}(G)$ does not contain $L^{2}(G)$ , so the Fourier transform of general $L^{2}$ -functions on G is "not" given by any kind of integration formula (or really any explicit formula).
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] To define the $L^{2}$ Fourier transform one has to resort to some technical trick such as starting on a dense subspace like the continuous functions with compact support and then extending the isometry by continuity to the whole space.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This unitary extension of the Fourier transform is what we mean by the Fourier transform on the space of square integrable functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The dual group also has an inverse Fourier transform in its own right; it can be characterized as the inverse (or adjoint, since it is unitary) of the $L^{2}$ Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This is the content of the $L^{2}$ Fourier inversion formula which follows.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] In the case $G=\mathbb {T}$ the dual group ${\widehat {G}}$ is naturally isomorphic to the group of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ and the Fourier transform specializes to the computation of coefficients of Fourier series of periodic functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] If G is a finite group, we recover the discrete Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Note that this case is very easy to prove directly.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] That G being compact implies ${\widehat {G}}$ is discrete or that G being discrete implies that ${\widehat {G}}$ is compact is an elementary consequence of the definition of the compact-open topology on ${\widehat {G}}$ and does not need Pontryagin duality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] One uses Pontryagin duality to prove the converses.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The Bohr compactification is defined for any topological group G , regardless of whether G is locally compact or abelian.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] One use made of Pontryagin duality between compact abelian groups and discrete abelian groups is to characterize the Bohr compactification of an arbitrary abelian *locally compact* topological group.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The *Bohr compactification* $B(G)$ of G is ${\widehat {H}}$ , where *H* has the group structure ${\widehat {G}}$ , but given the discrete topology.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Since the inclusion map $\iota :H\to {\widehat {G}}$ is continuous and a homomorphism, the dual morphism $G\sim {\widehat {\widehat {G}}}\to {\widehat {H}}$ is a morphism into a compact group which is easily shown to satisfy the requisite universal property.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Pontryagin duality can also profitably be considered functorially.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] In what follows, **LCA** is the category of locally compact abelian groups and continuous group homomorphisms.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] A categorical formulation of Pontryagin duality then states that the natural transformation between the identity functor on **LCA** and the double dual functor is an isomorphism.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Unwinding the notion of a natural transformation, this means that the maps $G\to \operatorname {Hom} (\operatorname {Hom} (G,T),T)$ are isomorphisms for any locally compact abelian group G , and these isomorphisms are functorial in G .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This isomorphism is analogous to the double dual of finite-dimensional vector spaces (a special case, for real and complex vector spaces).
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] An immediate consequence of this formulation is another common categorical formulation of Pontryagin duality: the dual group functor is an equivalence of categories from **LCA** to **LCA**op.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The duality interchanges the subcategories of discrete groups and compact groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] If R is a ring and G is a left R –module, the dual group ${\widehat {G}}$ will become a right R –module; in this way we can also see that discrete left R –modules will be Pontryagin dual to compact right R –modules.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The ring ${\text{End}}(G)$ of endomorphisms in **LCA** is changed by duality into its opposite ring (change the multiplication to the other order).
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] For example, if G is an infinite cyclic discrete group, ${\widehat {G}}$ is a circle group: the former has ${\text{End}}(G)=\mathbb {Z}$ so this is true also of the latter.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Generalizations of Pontryagin duality are constructed in two main directions: for commutative topological groups that are not locally compact, and for noncommutative topological groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The theories in these two cases are very different.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] When G is a Hausdorff abelian topological group, the group ${\widehat {G}}$ with the compact-open topology is a Hausdorff abelian topological group and the natural mapping from G to its double-dual ${\widehat {\widehat {G}}}$ makes sense.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] If this mapping is an isomorphism, it is said that G satisfies Pontryagin duality (or that G is a *reflexive group*, or a *reflective group*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This has been extended in a number of directions beyond the case that G is locally compact.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] In particular, Samuel Kaplan showed in 1948 and 1950 that arbitrary products and countable inverse limits of locally compact (Hausdorff) abelian groups satisfy Pontryagin duality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Note that an infinite product of locally compact non-compact spaces is not locally compact.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Later, in 1975, Rangachari Venkataraman showed, among other facts, that every open subgroup of an abelian topological group which satisfies Pontryagin duality itself satisfies Pontryagin duality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] More recently, Sergio Ardanza-Trevijano and María Jesús Chasco have extended the results of Kaplan mentioned above.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] They showed that direct and inverse limits of sequences of abelian groups satisfying Pontryagin duality also satisfy Pontryagin duality if the groups are metrizable or $k_{\omega }$ -spaces but not necessarily locally compact, provided some extra conditions are satisfied by the sequences.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] However, there is a fundamental aspect that changes if we want to consider Pontryagin duality beyond the locally compact case.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] As a corollary, all non-locally compact examples of Pontryagin duality are groups where the pairing $G\times {\widehat {G}}\to \mathbb {T}$ is not (jointly) continuous.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Another way to generalize Pontryagin duality to wider classes of commutative topological groups is to endow the dual group ${\widehat {G}}$ with a bit different topology, namely the *topology of uniform convergence on totally bounded sets*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The groups satisfying the identity $G\cong {\widehat {\widehat {G}}}$ under this assumption are called *stereotype groups*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This class is also very wide (and it contains locally compact abelian groups), but it is narrower than the class of reflective groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Smith noticed that Banach spaces and reflexive spaces, being considered as topological groups (with the additive group operation), satisfy Pontryagin duality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Brauner showed that this result can be extended to the class of all quasi-complete barreled spaces (in particular, to all Fréchet spaces).
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The spaces of this class are called stereotype spaces, and the corresponding theory found a series of applications in Functional analysis and Geometry, including the generalization of Pontryagin duality for non-commutative topological groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] For non-commutative locally compact groups G the classical Pontryagin construction stops working for various reasons, in particular, because the characters don't always separate the points of G , and the irreducible representations of G are not always one-dimensional.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] At the same time it is not clear how to introduce multiplication on the set of irreducible unitary representations of G , and it is even not clear whether this set is a good choice for the role of the dual object for G .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] So the problem of constructing duality in this situation requires complete rethinking.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The second type theories were historically the first: soon after Pontryagin's work Tadao Tannaka (1938) and Mark Krein (1949) constructed a duality theory for arbitrary compact groups known now as the Tannaka–Krein duality.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] In this theory the dual object for a group G is not a group but a category of its representations $\Pi (G)$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] The theories of first type appeared later and the key example for them was the duality theory for finite groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] Kac, Michel Enock, and Jean-Marie Schwartz built a general theory of this type for all locally compact groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] From the 1980s the research in this area was resumed after the discovery of quantum groups, to which the constructed theories began to be actively transferred.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] These theories are formulated in the language of C*-algebras, or Von Neumann algebras, and one of its variants is the recent theory of locally compact quantum groups.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] One of the drawbacks of these general theories, however, is that in them the objects generalizing the concept of a group are not Hopf algebras in the usual algebraic sense.
[src:harmonic-analysis/pontryagin-duality] This deficiency can be corrected (for some classes of groups) within the framework of duality theories constructed on the basis of the notion of envelope of topological algebra.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] A **wavelet** is a wave-like oscillation with an amplitude that begins at zero, increases or decreases, and then returns to zero one or more times.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelets are termed a "brief oscillation".
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] A taxonomy of wavelets has been established, based on the number and direction of its pulses.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelets are imbued with specific properties that make them useful for signal processing.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For example, a wavelet could be created to have a frequency of middle C and a short duration of roughly one tenth of a second.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] If this wavelet were to be convolved with a signal created from the recording of a melody, then the resulting signal would be useful for determining when the middle C note appeared in the song.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Mathematically, a wavelet correlates with a signal if a portion of the signal is similar.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Correlation is at the core of many practical wavelet applications.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] As a mathematical tool, wavelets can be used to extract information from many kinds of data, including audio signals and images.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Sets of wavelets are needed to analyze data fully.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] "Complementary" wavelets decompose a signal without gaps or overlaps so that the decomposition process is mathematically reversible.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Thus, sets of complementary wavelets are useful in wavelet-based compression/decompression algorithms, where it is desirable to recover the original information with minimal loss.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In formal terms, this representation is a wavelet series representation of a square-integrable function with respect to either a complete, orthonormal set of basis functions, or an overcomplete set or frame of a vector space, for the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This is accomplished through coherent states.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In classical physics, the diffraction phenomenon is described by the Huygens–Fresnel principle that treats each point in a propagating wavefront as a collection of individual spherical wavelets.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The characteristic bending pattern is most pronounced when a wave from a coherent source (such as a laser) encounters a slit/aperture that is comparable in size to its wavelength.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This is due to the addition, or interference, of different points on the wavefront (or, equivalently, each wavelet) that travel by paths of different lengths to the registering surface.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Multiple, closely spaced openings (e.g., a diffraction grating), can result in a complex pattern of varying intensity.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The word *wavelet* has been used for decades in digital signal processing and exploration geophysics.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The equivalent French word *ondelette* meaning "small wave" was used by Jean Morlet and Alex Grossmann in the early 1980s.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelet theory is applicable to several subjects.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] All wavelet transforms may be considered forms of time-frequency representation for continuous-time (analog) signals and so are related to harmonic analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Discrete wavelet transform (continuous in time) of a discrete-time (sampled) signal by using discrete-time filterbanks of dyadic (octave band) configuration is a wavelet approximation to that signal.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The coefficients of such a filter bank are called the shift and scaling coefficients in wavelets nomenclature.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] These filterbanks may contain either finite impulse response (FIR) or infinite impulse response (IIR) filters.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The wavelets forming a continuous wavelet transform (CWT) are subject to the uncertainty principle of Fourier analysis respective sampling theory: given a signal with some event in it, one cannot assign simultaneously an exact time and frequency response scale to that event.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The product of the uncertainties of time and frequency response scale has a lower bound.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Thus, in the scaleogram of a continuous wavelet transform of this signal, such an event marks an entire region in the time-scale plane, instead of just one point.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Also, discrete wavelet bases may be considered in the context of other forms of the uncertainty principle.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelet transforms are broadly divided into three classes: continuous, discrete and multiresolution-based.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In continuous wavelet transforms, a given signal of finite energy is projected on a continuous family of frequency bands (or similar subspaces of the *Lp* function space *L*2(**R**) ).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For instance the signal may be represented on every frequency band of the form [*f*, 2*f*] for all positive frequencies *f* > 0.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Then, the original signal can be reconstructed by a suitable integration over all the resulting frequency components.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The frequency bands or subspaces (sub-bands) are scaled versions of a subspace at scale 1.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This subspace in turn is in most situations generated by the shifts of one generating function ψ in *L*2(**R**), the *mother wavelet*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For the example of the scale one frequency band [1, 2] this function is $\psi (t)=2\,\operatorname {sinc} (2t)-\,\operatorname {sinc} (t)={\frac {\sin(2\pi t)-\sin(\pi t)}{\pi t}}$ with the (normalized) sinc function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The subspace of scale *a* or frequency band [1/*a*, 2/*a*] is generated by the functions (sometimes called *child wavelets*) $\psi _{a,b}(t)={\frac {1}{\sqrt {a}}}\psi \left({\frac {t-b}{a}}\right),$ where *a* is positive and defines the scale and *b* is any real number and defines the shift.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The pair (*a*, *b*) defines a point in the right halfplane **R**+ × **R**.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For the analysis of the signal *x*, one can assemble the wavelet coefficients into a scaleogram of the signal.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] It is computationally impossible to analyze a signal using all wavelet coefficients, so one may wonder if it is sufficient to pick a discrete subset of the upper halfplane to be able to reconstruct a signal from the corresponding wavelet coefficients.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] One such system is the affine system for some real parameters *a* > 1, *b* > 0.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The corresponding discrete subset of the halfplane consists of all the points (*am*, *nb am*) with *m*, *n* in **Z**.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In any discretised wavelet transform, there are only a finite number of wavelet coefficients for each bounded rectangular region in the upper halfplane.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Still, each coefficient requires the evaluation of an integral.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In special situations this numerical complexity can be avoided if the scaled and shifted wavelets form a multiresolution analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This means that there has to exist an auxiliary function, the *father wavelet* φ in *L*2(**R**), and that *a* is an integer.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] A typical choice is *a* = 2 and *b* = 1.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The most famous pair of father and mother wavelets is the Daubechies 4-tap wavelet.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Note that not every orthonormal discrete wavelet basis can be associated to a multiresolution analysis; for example, the Journe wavelet admits no multiresolution analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In analogy to the sampling theorem one may conclude that the space *Vm* with sampling distance 2*m* more or less covers the frequency baseband from 0 to 1/2*m*-1.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] As orthogonal complement, *Wm* roughly covers the band [1/2*m*−1, 1/2*m*].
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Both pairs of identities form the basis for the algorithm of the fast wavelet transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For processing temporal signals in real time, it is essential that the wavelet filters do not access signal values from the future as well as that minimal temporal latencies can be obtained.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Time-causal wavelets representations have been developed by Szu et al and Lindeberg, with the latter method also involving a memory-efficient time-recursive implementation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For practical applications, and for efficiency reasons, one prefers continuously differentiable functions with compact support as mother (prototype) wavelet (functions).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Being in this space ensures that one can formulate the conditions of zero mean and square norm one: $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }\psi (t)\,dt=0$ is the condition for zero mean, and $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }|\psi (t)|^{2}\,dt=1$ is the condition for square norm one.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For *ψ* to be a wavelet for the continuous wavelet transform (see there for exact statement), the mother wavelet must satisfy an admissibility criterion (loosely speaking, a kind of half-differentiability) in order to get a stably invertible transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For the discrete wavelet transform, one needs at least the condition that the wavelet series is a representation of the identity in the space *L*2(**R**).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Most constructions of discrete WT make use of the multiresolution analysis, which defines the wavelet by a scaling function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This scaling function itself is a solution to a functional equation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For the continuous WT, the pair (*a*,*b*) varies over the full half-plane **R**+ × **R**; for the discrete WT this pair varies over a discrete subset of it, which is also called *affine group*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] These functions are often incorrectly referred to as the basis functions of the (continuous) transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In fact, as in the continuous Fourier transform, there is no basis in the continuous wavelet transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Time-frequency interpretation uses a subtly different formulation (after Delprat).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The wavelet transform is often compared with the Fourier transform, in which signals are represented as a sum of sinusoids.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In fact, the Fourier transform can be viewed as a special case of the continuous wavelet transform with the choice of the mother wavelet $\psi (t)=e^{-2\pi it}$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The main difference in general is that wavelets are localized in both time and frequency whereas the standard Fourier transform is only localized in frequency.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The short-time Fourier transform (STFT) is similar to the wavelet transform, in that it is also time and frequency localized, but there are issues with the frequency/time resolution trade-off.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Multiplication with a rectangular window in the time domain corresponds to convolution with a $\operatorname {sinc} (\Delta _{t}\omega )$ function in the frequency domain, resulting in spurious ringing artifacts for short/localized temporal windows.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] With the continuous-time Fourier transform, $\Delta _{t}\to \infty$ and this convolution is with a delta function in Fourier space, resulting in the true Fourier transform of the signal $x(t)$ .
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The window function may be some other apodizing filter, such as a Gaussian.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The choice of windowing function will affect the approximation error relative to the true Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] A given resolution cell's time-bandwidth product may not be exceeded with the STFT.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] All STFT basis elements maintain a uniform spectral and temporal support for all temporal shifts or offsets, thereby attaining an equal resolution in time for lower and higher frequencies.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The resolution is purely determined by the sampling width.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In contrast, the wavelet transform's multiresolutional properties enables large temporal supports for lower frequencies while maintaining short temporal widths for higher frequencies by the scaling properties of the wavelet transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This property extends conventional time-frequency analysis into time-scale analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The discrete wavelet transform is less computationally complex, taking O(*N*) time as compared to O(*N* log *N*) for the fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This computational advantage is not inherent to the transform, but reflects the choice of a logarithmic division of frequency, in contrast to the equally spaced frequency divisions of the FFT which uses the same basis functions as the discrete Fourier transform (DFT).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This complexity only applies when the filter size has no relation to the signal size.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] A wavelet without compact support such as the Shannon wavelet would require O(*N*2).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] An orthogonal wavelet is entirely defined by the scaling filter – a low-pass finite impulse response (FIR) filter of length 2*N* and sum 1.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In biorthogonal wavelets, separate decomposition and reconstruction filters are defined.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For analysis with orthogonal wavelets the high pass filter is calculated as the quadrature mirror filter of the low pass, and reconstruction filters are the time reverse of the decomposition filters.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Daubechies and Symlet wavelets can be defined by the scaling filter.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelets are defined by the wavelet function ψ(*t*) (i.e. the mother wavelet) and scaling function φ(*t*) (also called father wavelet) in the time domain.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The wavelet function is in effect a band-pass filter and scaling that for each level halves its bandwidth.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This creates the problem that in order to cover the entire spectrum, an infinite number of levels would be required.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The scaling function filters the lowest level of the transform and ensures all the spectrum is covered.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For a wavelet with compact support, φ(*t*) can be considered finite in length and is equivalent to the scaling filter *g*.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The wavelet only has a time domain representation as the wavelet function ψ(*t*).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For instance, Mexican hat wavelets can be defined by a wavelet function.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] See a list of a few continuous wavelets.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The development of wavelets can be linked to several separate trains of thought, starting with Alfréd Haar's work in the early 20th century.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Later work by Dennis Gabor yielded Gabor atoms (1946), which are constructed similarly to wavelets, and applied to similar purposes.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The JPEG 2000 standard was developed from 1997 to 2000 by a Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) committee chaired by Touradj Ebrahimi (later the JPEG president).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In contrast to the DCT algorithm used by the original JPEG format, JPEG 2000 instead uses discrete wavelet transform (DWT) algorithms.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] It uses the CDF 9/7 wavelet transform (developed by Ingrid Daubechies in 1992) for its lossy compression algorithm, and the Le Gall–Tabatabai (LGT) 5/3 discrete-time filter bank (developed by Didier Le Gall and Ali J.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Tabatabai in 1988) for its lossless compression algorithm.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] JPEG 2000 technology, which includes the Motion JPEG 2000 extension, was selected as the video coding standard for digital cinema in 2004.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] A wavelet is a mathematical function used to divide a given function or continuous-time signal into different scale components.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Usually one can assign a frequency range to each scale component.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Each scale component can then be studied with a resolution that matches its scale.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] A wavelet transform is the representation of a function by wavelets.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The wavelets are scaled and translated copies (known as "daughter wavelets") of a finite-length or fast-decaying oscillating waveform (known as the "mother wavelet").
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelet transforms have advantages over traditional Fourier transforms for representing functions that have discontinuities and sharp peaks, and for accurately deconstructing and reconstructing finite, non-periodic and/or non-stationary signals.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelet transforms are classified into discrete wavelet transforms (DWTs) and continuous wavelet transforms (CWTs).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Note that both DWT and CWT are continuous-time (analog) transforms.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] They can be used to represent continuous-time (analog) signals.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] CWTs operate over every possible scale and translation whereas DWTs use a specific subset of scale and translation values or representation grid.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] There are a large number of wavelet transforms each suitable for different applications.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] There are a number of generalized transforms of which the wavelet transform is a special case.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For example, Yosef Joseph Segman introduced scale into the Heisenberg group, giving rise to a continuous transform space that is a function of time, scale, and frequency.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] The CWT is a two-dimensional slice through the resulting 3d time-scale-frequency volume.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Another example of a generalized transform is the chirplet transform in which the CWT is also a two dimensional slice through the chirplet transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] An important application area for generalized transforms involves systems in which high frequency resolution is crucial.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For example, darkfield electron optical transforms intermediate between direct and reciprocal space have been widely used in the harmonic analysis of atom clustering, i.e. in the study of crystals and crystal defects.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Fractional wavelet transform (FRWT) is a generalization of the classical wavelet transform in the fractional Fourier transform domains.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This transform is capable of providing the time- and fractional-domain information simultaneously and representing signals in the time-fractional-frequency plane.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Generally, an approximation to DWT is used for data compression if a signal is already sampled, and the CWT for signal analysis.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Thus, DWT approximation is commonly used in engineering and computer science, and the CWT in scientific research.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Like some other transforms, wavelet transforms can be used to transform data, then encode the transformed data, resulting in effective compression.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] For example, JPEG 2000 is an image compression standard that uses biorthogonal wavelets.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This means that although the frame is overcomplete, it is a *tight frame* (see types of frames of a vector space), and the same frame functions (except for conjugation in the case of complex wavelets) are used for both analysis and synthesis, i.e., in both the forward and inverse transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] A related use is for smoothing/denoising data based on wavelet coefficient thresholding, also called wavelet shrinkage.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] By adaptively thresholding the wavelet coefficients that correspond to undesired frequency components smoothing and/or denoising operations can be performed.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelet transforms are also starting to be used for communication applications.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelet OFDM is the basic modulation scheme used in HD-PLC (a power line communications technology developed by Panasonic), and in one of the optional modes included in the IEEE 1901 standard.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelet OFDM can achieve deeper notches than traditional FFT OFDM, and wavelet OFDM does not require a guard interval (which usually represents significant overhead in FFT OFDM systems).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Often, signals can be represented well as a sum of sinusoids.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] However, consider a non-continuous signal with an abrupt discontinuity; this signal can still be represented as a sum of sinusoids, but requires an infinite number, which is an observation known as Gibbs phenomenon.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This, then, requires an infinite number of Fourier coefficients, which is not practical for many applications, such as compression.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Wavelets are more useful for describing these signals with discontinuities because of their time-localized behavior (both Fourier and wavelet transforms are frequency-localized, but wavelets have an additional time-localization property).
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Because of this, many types of signals in practice may be non-sparse in the Fourier domain, but very sparse in the wavelet domain.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This is particularly useful in signal reconstruction, especially in the recently popular field of compressed sensing.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] (Note that the short-time Fourier transform (STFT) is also localized in time and frequency, but there are often problems with the frequency-time resolution trade-off.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] This motivates why wavelet transforms are now being adopted for a vast number of applications, often replacing the conventional Fourier transform.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Many areas of physics have seen this paradigm shift, including molecular dynamics, chaos theory, ab initio calculations, astrophysics, gravitational wave transient data analysis, density-matrix localisation, seismology, optics, turbulence and quantum mechanics.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] In computer vision and image processing, the notion of scale space representation and Gaussian derivative operators is regarded as a canonical multi-scale representation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Suppose we measure a noisy signal $x=s+v$ , where s represents the signal and v represents the noise.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Let the wavelet transform of x be $y=W^{T}x=W^{T}s+W^{T}v=p+z$ , where $p=W^{T}s$ is the wavelet transform of the signal component and $z=W^{T}v$ is the wavelet transform of the noise component.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Since W is orthogonal, the estimation problem amounts to recovery of a signal in iid Gaussian noise.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] As p is sparse, one method is to apply a Gaussian mixture model for p .
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] By setting coefficients that fall below a shrinkage threshold to zero, once the inverse transform is applied, an expectedly small amount of signal is lost due to the sparsity assumption.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Typically, the above-threshold coefficients are not modified during this process.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Some algorithms for wavelet-based denoising may attenuate larger coefficients as well, based on a statistical estimate of the amount of noise expected to be removed by such an attenuation.
[src:harmonic-analysis/wavelet] Agarwal et al. proposed wavelet based advanced linear and nonlinear methods to construct and investigate Climate as complex networks at different timescales.
